lines until the questions

00:12:49.240 --> 00:12:50.073
at the end.

00:12:50.073 --> 00:12:52.100
We begin with an opening
argument, 20 minutes,

00:12:52.100 --> 00:12:52.990
to Professor Craig.

00:12:52.990 --> 00:12:53.823
Professor?

00:12:57.439 --> 00:13:00.439
[audience applause]

00:13:07.150 --> 00:13:08.810
&gt;&gt; Good evening.

00:13:08.810 --> 00:13:11.176
I am very excited to be participating

00:13:11.176 --> 00:13:13.150
in this debate tonight.

00:13:13.150 --> 00:13:16.290
Jan and I used to sit
in those very bleachers

00:13:16.290 --> 00:13:19.200
right over there watching our son John

00:13:19.200 --> 00:13:21.410
run up and down this court as a forward

00:13:21.410 --> 00:13:23.050
on the Biola Eagles.

00:13:23.050 --> 00:13:26.820
And so I feel like I'm playing
at the home court tonight.

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:29.580
And I wanna commend Mr.
Hitchens for his willingness

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:31.640
to come into this den of lambs

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:33.853
and to defend his views tonight.

00:13:35.170 --> 00:13:38.460
On the other hand, if
I know Biola students,

00:13:38.460 --> 00:13:42.020
I suspected a good many of
you, when you came in tonight,

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:45.327
said to yourself, "I'm gonna
check my own views at the door,

00:13:45.327 --> 00:13:48.247
"and I'm gonna assess the
arguments as objectively

00:13:48.247 --> 00:13:49.660
"as possible."

00:13:49.660 --> 00:13:52.360
I welcome that challenge.

00:13:52.360 --> 00:13:55.740
You see the question of God's
existence is of interest

00:13:55.740 --> 00:14:00.360
not only to religion,
but also to philosophy.

00:14:00.360 --> 00:14:02.530
Now Mr. Hitchens has made it clear that he

00:14:02.530 --> 00:14:05.820
despises and disdains religion,

00:14:05.820 --> 00:14:10.210
but presumably he is not so
contemptuous of philosophy.

00:14:10.210 --> 00:14:12.920
Therefore, as a professional philosopher,

00:14:12.920 --> 00:14:16.490
I'm going to approach tonight's
question philosophically,

00:14:16.490 --> 00:14:19.680
from the standpoint of
reason and argument.

00:14:19.680 --> 00:14:22.230
I'm convinced that there
are better arguments

00:14:22.230 --> 00:14:25.350
for theism than for atheism.

00:14:25.350 --> 00:14:27.680
So, in tonight's debate,
I'm going to defend

00:14:27.680 --> 00:14:29.720
two basic contentions.

00:14:29.720 --> 00:14:34.720
First, that there's no good
arguments that atheism is true.

00:14:35.510 --> 00:14:38.080
And secondly, that
there are good arguments

00:14:38.080 --> 00:14:40.143
that theism is true.

00:14:41.260 --> 00:14:44.513
Now, notice carefully
the circumscribed limits

00:14:44.513 --> 00:14:46.960
of those contentions.

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:49.740
We're not here tonight
to debate the social

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:53.750
impact of religion or
Old Testament ethics,

00:14:53.750 --> 00:14:55.700
or Biblical inerrancy.

00:14:55.700 --> 00:14:58.470
All interesting and
important topics, no doubt,

00:14:58.470 --> 00:15:00.880
but not the subject of tonight's debate,

00:15:00.880 --> 00:15:04.560
which is the existence of God.

00:15:04.560 --> 00:15:06.730
Consider, then, my first contention,

00:15:06.730 --> 00:15:10.679
that there's no good argument
that atheism is true.

00:15:10.679 --> 00:15:13.220
Atheists have tried for centuries

00:15:13.220 --> 00:15:15.330
to disprove the existence of God,

00:15:15.330 --> 00:15:17.060
but no one's ever been able to come up

00:15:17.060 --> 00:15:18.870
with a successful argument.

00:15:18.870 --> 00:15:22.230
So, rather than attack
strong men at this point,

00:15:22.230 --> 00:15:25.030
I'll just wait to hear
Mr. Hitchens present his

00:15:25.030 --> 00:15:28.360
arguments against God's
existence, and then

00:15:28.360 --> 00:15:31.300
I'll respond to them in my next speech.

00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:34.370
In the meantime, let's turn
to my second main contention,

00:15:34.370 --> 00:15:38.020
that there are good arguments
that theism is true.

00:15:38.020 --> 00:15:42.590
On your program insert, I
outlined some of those arguments.

00:15:42.590 --> 00:15:46.163
Number one, the cosmological argument.

00:15:47.096 --> 00:15:50.370
The question of why anything at all exists

00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:54.373
is the most profound
question of philosophy.

00:15:54.373 --> 00:15:57.167
The philosopher Derek Parfit says,

00:15:57.167 --> 00:16:01.547
"No question is more sublime
than why there is a universe,

00:16:01.547 --> 00:16:05.430
"why there is anything
rather than nothing."

00:16:05.430 --> 00:16:07.620
Typically atheists have
answered this question

00:16:07.620 --> 00:16:12.230
by saying that the universe
is just eternal and uncaused.

00:16:12.230 --> 00:16:14.600
But there are good reasons,
both philosophically

00:16:14.600 --> 00:16:17.480
and scientifically, to
think that the universe

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:19.640
began to exist.

00:16:19.640 --> 00:16:23.690
Philosophically, the idea of
an infinite past seems absurd.

00:16:23.690 --> 00:16:27.900
Just think about it: If the
universe never began to exist,

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:30.330
that means that the number of past events

00:16:30.330 --> 00:16:34.060
in the history of the
universe is infinite.

00:16:34.060 --> 00:16:36.930
But mathematicians recognize
that the existence of an

00:16:36.930 --> 00:16:39.870
actually infinite number of things leads

00:16:39.870 --> 00:16:41.640
to self-contradictions.

00:16:41.640 --> 00:16:46.180
For example, what is
infinity minus infinity?

00:16:46.180 --> 00:16:49.810
Well, mathematically you get
self-contradictory answers.

00:16:49.810 --> 00:16:53.200
This shows that infinity is
just an idea in your mind,

00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:55.930
but not something that exists in reality.

00:16:55.930 --> 00:16:58.600
David Hilbert, perhaps the
greatest mathematician of the

00:16:58.600 --> 00:17:01.757
20th century, wrote,
"The infinite is nowhere

00:17:01.757 --> 00:17:03.747
"to be found in reality.

00:17:03.747 --> 00:17:07.467
"It neither exists in nature,
nor provides a legitimate

00:17:07.467 --> 00:17:09.527
"basis for rational thought.

00:17:09.527 --> 00:17:12.957
"The role that remains
for the infinite to play

00:17:12.957 --> 00:17:15.347
"is solely that of an idea."

00:17:16.550 --> 00:17:20.170
But that entails that since
past events are not just ideas

00:17:20.170 --> 00:17:24.540
but are real, the number of
past events must be finite,

00:17:24.540 --> 00:17:28.030
therefore the series of past
events can't go back forever.

00:17:28.030 --> 00:17:31.583
Rather, the universe
must have begun to exist.

00:17:32.670 --> 00:17:35.290
This conclusion has been
confirmed by remarkable

00:17:35.290 --> 00:17:38.680
discoveries in astronomy and astrophysics.

00:17:38.680 --> 00:17:41.710
In one of the most startling
developments of modern science

00:17:41.710 --> 00:17:45.990
we now have pretty strong
evidence that the universe is not

00:17:45.990 --> 00:17:50.060
eternal in the past but had
an absolute beginning about

00:17:50.060 --> 00:17:53.940
13 billion years ago
in a cataclysmic event

00:17:53.940 --> 00:17:55.840
known as the Big Bang.

00:17:55.840 --> 00:17:59.550
What makes the Big Bang so
startling is that it represents

00:17:59.550 --> 00:18:03.800
the origin of the universe
from literally nothing,

00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:07.050
for all matter and energy, even physical

00:18:07.050 --> 00:18:12.050
space and time themselves, came
into being at the Big Bang.

00:18:12.520 --> 00:18:15.747
As the physicist P.C.W. Davies explains,

00:18:15.747 --> 00:18:18.797
"The coming into being of
the universe, as discussed in

00:18:18.797 --> 00:18:22.507
"modern science, is not just
a matter of imposing some

00:18:22.507 --> 00:18:26.937
"sort of organization upon
a previous incoherent state

00:18:26.937 --> 00:18:30.447
"but literally the coming into being of

00:18:30.447 --> 00:18:33.567
"all physical things from nothing."

00:18:34.540 --> 00:18:38.200
Now, this puts the atheist
in a very awkward position.

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:41.417
As Anthony Kenny of
Oxford University urges,

00:18:41.417 --> 00:18:43.337
"A proponent of the Big Bang theory,

00:18:43.337 --> 00:18:45.827
"at least if he is an atheist,

00:18:45.827 --> 00:18:48.497
"must believe that the universe came

00:18:48.497 --> 00:18:52.470
"from nothing and by nothing."

00:18:52.470 --> 00:18:54.890
But surely that doesn't make sense.

00:18:54.890 --> 00:18:57.570
Out of nothing, nothing comes.

00:18:57.570 --> 00:18:59.620
So why does the universe exist,

00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:02.870
instead of just nothing,
where did it come from?

00:19:02.870 --> 00:19:05.810
There must have been a cause which brought

00:19:05.810 --> 00:19:08.300
the universe into being.

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:11.980
Now as the cause of space and time,

00:19:11.980 --> 00:19:16.980
this being must be an
uncaused, timeless, spaceless,

00:19:17.240 --> 00:19:20.930
immaterial being of unfathomable power.

00:19:20.930 --> 00:19:24.440
Moreover, it must be personal as well.

00:19:24.440 --> 00:19:25.440
Why?

00:19:25.440 --> 00:19:30.200
Because the cause must
be beyond space and time,

00:19:30.200 --> 00:19:33.650
therefore it cannot be
physical or material.

00:19:33.650 --> 00:19:35.840
Now there are only two
kinds of things that fit

00:19:35.840 --> 00:19:39.640
that description: either
an abstract object,

00:19:39.640 --> 00:19:44.240
like numbers, or else a personal mind.

00:19:44.240 --> 00:19:48.030
But abstract objects can't cause anything.

00:19:48.030 --> 00:19:49.940
Therefore it follows that the cause of the

00:19:49.940 --> 00:19:54.670
universe is a transcendent,
intelligent mind.

00:19:54.670 --> 00:19:57.630
Thus the cosmological argument gives us a

00:19:57.630 --> 00:20:01.249
personal creator of the universe.

00:20:01.249 --> 00:20:04.463
Two, the teleological argument.

00:20:05.430 --> 00:20:08.470
In recent decades scientists
have been stunned by the

00:20:08.470 --> 00:20:10.640
discovery that the initial conditions

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:14.220
of the Big Bang were fine
tuned for the existence

00:20:14.220 --> 00:20:17.290
of intelligent life with a precision

00:20:17.290 --> 00:20:21.950
and delicacy that literally
defied human comprehension.

00:20:21.950 --> 00:20:24.650
This fine tuning is of two sorts:

00:20:24.650 --> 00:20:27.550
first, when the laws
of nature are expressed

00:20:27.550 --> 00:20:29.540
as mathematical equations,

00:20:29.540 --> 00:20:31.869
you find appearing in
them certain constants

00:20:31.869 --> 00:20:34.546
like the gravitational constant.

00:20:34.546 --> 00:20:38.900
These constants are not
determined by the laws of nature.

00:20:38.900 --> 00:20:41.160
The laws of nature are consistent with

00:20:41.160 --> 00:20:44.610
a wide range of values
for these constants.

00:20:44.610 --> 00:20:47.520
Second, in addition to
these constants there

00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:50.440
are certain arbitrary quantities put in

00:20:50.440 --> 00:20:54.700
as initial conditions on which
the laws of nature operate.

00:20:54.700 --> 00:20:58.170
For example, the amount of
entropy or the balance between

00:20:58.170 --> 00:21:01.222
matter and antimatter in the universe.

00:21:01.222 --> 00:21:04.210
Now all of these constants and quantities

00:21:04.210 --> 00:21:07.770
fall into an extraordinarily narrow range

00:21:07.770 --> 00:21:10.370
of life-permitting values.

00:21:10.370 --> 00:21:12.280
Were these constants or quantities

00:21:12.280 --> 00:21:15.330
to be altered by less
than a hair's breath,

00:21:15.330 --> 00:21:20.330
the balance would be destroyed
and life would not exist.

00:21:20.580 --> 00:21:22.400
To give just one example:

00:21:22.400 --> 00:21:26.420
The atomic weak force, if it
were altered by as little as

00:21:26.420 --> 00:21:30.022
one part out of 10 to the 100th power

00:21:30.022 --> 00:21:34.690
would not have permitted a
life-permitting universe.

00:21:34.690 --> 00:21:37.190
Now there are three
possible explanations of

00:21:37.190 --> 00:21:41.120
this remarkable fine
tuning: physical necessity,

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:43.573
chance, or design.

00:21:44.450 --> 00:21:47.100
Now it can't be due to
physical necessity because the

00:21:47.100 --> 00:21:49.750
constants and quantities are independent

00:21:49.750 --> 00:21:51.730
of the laws of nature.

00:21:51.730 --> 00:21:54.684
In fact string theory
predicts that there are around

00:21:54.684 --> 00:21:58.810
10 to the 500th power different possible

00:21:58.810 --> 00:22:02.900
universes consistent with nature's laws.

00:22:02.900 --> 00:22:06.340
So could the fine tuning be due to chance?

00:22:06.340 --> 00:22:08.300
Well, the problem with this alternative

00:22:08.300 --> 00:22:11.140
is that the odds against the fine tunings

00:22:11.140 --> 00:22:14.805
occurring by accident
are so incomprehensibly

00:22:14.805 --> 00:22:18.210
great that they cannot
be reasonably faced.

00:22:18.210 --> 00:22:21.162
The probability that all the constants

00:22:21.162 --> 00:22:25.310
and quantities would fall
by chance alone into the

00:22:25.310 --> 00:22:30.020
infinitesimal life-permitting
range is vanishingly small.

00:22:30.020 --> 00:22:33.370
We now know that
life-prohibiting universes

00:22:33.370 --> 00:22:38.210
are vastly more probable than
any life-permitting universe.

00:22:38.210 --> 00:22:41.390
So if the universe were
the product of chance,

00:22:41.390 --> 00:22:45.203
the odds are overwhelming that
it would be life-prohibiting.

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:49.420
In order to rescue the
alternative of chance,

00:22:49.420 --> 00:22:51.640
its proponents have therefore been forced

00:22:51.640 --> 00:22:55.660
to resort to a radical
metaphysical hypothesis.

00:22:55.660 --> 00:22:59.570
Namely, that there
exists an infinite number

00:22:59.570 --> 00:23:03.610
of randomly ordered,
undetectable universes

00:23:03.610 --> 00:23:06.270
composing a sort of world ensemble

00:23:06.270 --> 00:23:10.550
or multiverse of which our
universe is but a part.

00:23:10.550 --> 00:23:14.320
Somewhere in this infinite
world ensemble finely tuned

00:23:14.320 --> 00:23:17.070
universes will appear by chance alone

00:23:17.070 --> 00:23:20.460
and we happen to be one such world.

00:23:20.460 --> 00:23:24.380
Now wholly apart from the fact
that there's no independent

00:23:24.380 --> 00:23:27.620
evidence that such a world
ensemble even exists,

00:23:27.620 --> 00:23:31.140
the hypothesis faces a
devastating objection,

00:23:31.140 --> 00:23:36.140
namely, if our universe is
just a random member of an

00:23:36.280 --> 00:23:39.970
infinite world ensemble then
it is overwhelmingly more

00:23:39.970 --> 00:23:43.610
probably that we should be
observing a much different

00:23:43.610 --> 00:23:46.270
universe than what we in fact observe.

00:23:46.270 --> 00:23:49.010
Roger Penrose has calculated that it is

00:23:49.010 --> 00:23:52.770
inconceivably more probable
that our solar system

00:23:52.770 --> 00:23:56.220
should suddenly form
through a random collision

00:23:56.220 --> 00:24:00.220
of particles than that a finely
tuned universe should exist.

00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:03.930
Penrose calls it "utter
chicken feed" by comparison.

00:24:03.930 --> 00:24:07.940
So, if our universe were
just a random member of

00:24:07.940 --> 00:24:12.290
a world ensemble it is
inconceivably more probable

00:24:12.290 --> 00:24:15.040
that we should be
observing an orderly region

00:24:15.040 --> 00:24:18.080
no larger than our solar system.

00:24:18.080 --> 00:24:22.110
Observable universes like
those are simply much more

00:24:22.110 --> 00:24:25.730
plenteous in the world
ensemble than finely tuned

00:24:25.730 --> 00:24:30.220
worlds like ours and therefore
ought to be observed by us.

00:24:30.220 --> 00:24:32.726
Since we do not have such observations

00:24:32.726 --> 00:24:37.726
that fact strongly dis-confirms
the multiverse hypothesis.

00:24:38.820 --> 00:24:40.910
On atheism, at least, then it is highly

00:24:40.910 --> 00:24:45.069
probable that there is no world ensemble.

00:24:45.069 --> 00:24:48.070
The fine tuning of the
universe is therefore

00:24:48.070 --> 00:24:52.080
plausibly due neither to
physical necessity nor to chance.

00:24:52.080 --> 00:24:54.380
It therefore follows logically that

00:24:54.380 --> 00:24:57.400
the best explanation is design.

00:24:57.400 --> 00:24:59.540
Thus the teleological argument gives

00:24:59.540 --> 00:25:03.373
us an intelligent designer of the cosmos.

00:25:04.640 --> 00:25:06.923
Three, the moral argument.

00:25:07.990 --> 00:25:11.590
If God does not exist then objective moral

00:25:11.590 --> 00:25:13.866
values do not exist.

00:25:13.866 --> 00:25:17.340
By objective moral values
I mean moral values

00:25:17.340 --> 00:25:19.900
which are valid and
binding whether we believe

00:25:19.900 --> 00:25:21.420
in them or not.

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:24.010
Many theists and atheists
agree that if God

00:25:24.010 --> 00:25:27.150
does not exist then moral values are not

00:25:27.150 --> 00:25:29.670
objective in this way.

00:25:29.670 --> 00:25:33.617
Michael Ruse, a noted
philosopher of science, explains,

00:25:33.617 --> 00:25:35.737
"The position of the modern evolutionist

00:25:35.737 --> 00:25:39.197
"is that morality is a
biological adaptation,

00:25:39.197 --> 00:25:42.227
"no less than our hands
and feet and teeth.

00:25:42.227 --> 00:25:44.637
"Considered as a
rationally justifiable set

00:25:44.637 --> 00:25:49.467
"of claims about an objective
something, ethics is illusory.

00:25:49.467 --> 00:25:51.892
"I appreciate that when someone says,

00:25:51.892 --> 00:25:54.277
"'love thy neighbor as thyself,'

00:25:54.277 --> 00:25:57.607
"they think they are referring
above and beyond themselves.

00:25:57.607 --> 00:26:01.337
"Nevertheless, such reference
is truly without foundation.

00:26:01.337 --> 00:26:05.087
"Morality is just an aid to survival

00:26:05.087 --> 00:26:10.087
"and reproduction and any
deeper meaning is illusory."

00:26:12.140 --> 00:26:14.410
Like Professor Ruse I just don't see

00:26:14.410 --> 00:26:17.560
any reason to think that
in the absence of God,

00:26:17.560 --> 00:26:20.650
the morality which has emerged among these

00:26:20.650 --> 00:26:25.240
imperfectly evolved primates
we call Homo sapiens is

00:26:25.240 --> 00:26:29.710
objective, and here Mr.
Hitchens seems to agree with me.

00:26:29.710 --> 00:26:34.460
He says moral values are
just innate predispositions,

00:26:34.460 --> 00:26:37.240
ingrained into us by evolution.

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:39.890
Such predispositions,
he says, are inevitable

00:26:39.890 --> 00:26:44.070
for any animal endowed
with social instincts.

00:26:44.070 --> 00:26:47.810
On the atheistic view
then an action like rape

00:26:47.810 --> 00:26:51.280
is not socially advantageous and so in

00:26:51.280 --> 00:26:54.720
the course of human
development has become taboo,

00:26:54.720 --> 00:26:58.160
but that does absolutely
nothing to prove that rape is

00:26:58.160 --> 00:27:00.510
really morally wrong.

00:27:00.510 --> 00:27:02.720
On the atheistic view
there's nothing really

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:05.343
wrong with raping someone.

00:27:06.420 --> 00:27:09.800
But the problem is that
objective values do exist

00:27:09.800 --> 00:27:11.900
and deep down we all know it.

00:27:11.900 --> 00:27:14.400
In moral experience we apprehend

00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:17.880
a realm of objective
moral goods and evils.

00:27:17.880 --> 00:27:21.130
Actions like rape,
cruelty, and child abuse

00:27:21.130 --> 00:27:23.450
aren't just socially
unacceptable behavior,

00:27:23.450 --> 00:27:25.330
they're moral abominations.

00:27:25.330 --> 00:27:28.140
Some things, at least, are really wrong.

00:27:28.140 --> 00:27:31.020
Similarly love, equality,
and self-sacrifice

00:27:31.020 --> 00:27:32.750
are really good.

00:27:32.750 --> 00:27:36.320
But then it follows
logically and necessarily

00:27:36.320 --> 00:27:38.053
that God exists.

00:27:39.210 --> 00:27:42.970
Number four, the resurrection of Jesus.

00:27:42.970 --> 00:27:45.680
The historical person Jesus of Nazareth

00:27:45.680 --> 00:27:48.100
was a remarkable individual.

00:27:48.100 --> 00:27:50.560
Historians have reached
something of a consensus

00:27:50.560 --> 00:27:53.650
that the historical Jesus
came on the scene with an

00:27:53.650 --> 00:27:56.500
unprecedented sense of divine authority,

00:27:56.500 --> 00:28:00.870
the authority to stand
and speak in God's place.

00:28:00.870 --> 00:28:03.170
He claimed that in
Himself the Kingdom of God

00:28:03.170 --> 00:28:05.910
had come and as visible
demonstrations of this

00:28:05.910 --> 00:28:08.900
fact He carried out a
ministry of miracle working

00:28:08.900 --> 00:28:10.890
and exorcisms.

00:28:10.890 --> 00:28:12.510
But the supreme confirmation of

00:28:12.510 --> 00:28:15.570
His claim was His
resurrection from the dead.

00:28:15.570 --> 00:28:18.350
If Jesus did rise from the dead than

00:28:18.350 --> 00:28:20.810
it would seem that we
have a divine miracle

00:28:20.810 --> 00:28:25.440
on our hands and thus evidence
for the existence of God.

00:28:25.440 --> 00:28:28.180
Now most people probably
think that the resurrection of

00:28:28.180 --> 00:28:32.070
Jesus is something you just
believe in, by faith or not.

00:28:32.070 --> 00:28:34.520
But there are actually
three established facts

00:28:34.520 --> 00:28:36.940
recognized by the
majority of New Testament

00:28:36.940 --> 00:28:40.660
historians today which I
believe are best explained

00:28:40.660 --> 00:28:42.770
by the resurrection of Jesus.

00:28:42.770 --> 00:28:46.550
Fact number one: on the
Sunday after His crucifixion,

00:28:46.550 --> 00:28:50.260
Jesus' tomb was discovered
empty by a group

00:28:50.260 --> 00:28:52.000
of His women followers.

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:55.170
According to Jakob Kremer,
an Austrian specialist,

00:28:55.170 --> 00:28:59.740
by far most scholars hold
firmly to the reliability

00:28:59.740 --> 00:29:03.550
of the biblical statements
about the empty tomb.

00:29:03.550 --> 00:29:07.430
Fact number two: on separate
occasions different individuals

00:29:07.430 --> 00:29:10.730
in groups experienced appearances of Jesus

00:29:10.730 --> 00:29:12.870
alive after his death.

00:29:12.870 --> 00:29:14.590
According to the prominent New Testament

00:29:14.590 --> 00:29:18.140
critic Gerd LÃ¼demann, it
may be taken as historically

00:29:18.140 --> 00:29:21.567
certain that the disciples
had experiences after Jesus'

00:29:21.567 --> 00:29:26.567
death in which Jesus appeared
to them as the risen Christ.

00:29:27.210 --> 00:29:30.720
These appearances were
witnessed not only by believers

00:29:30.720 --> 00:29:35.720
but also by unbelievers,
skeptics, and even enemies.

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:39.750
Fact number three: the
original disciples suddenly

00:29:39.750 --> 00:29:42.350
came to believe in the
resurrection of Jesus

00:29:42.350 --> 00:29:45.790
despite having every
predisposition to the contrary.

00:29:45.790 --> 00:29:50.720
Jews had no belief in a dying,
much less rising Messiah.

00:29:50.720 --> 00:29:53.527
And Jewish beliefs about the
afterlife prohibited anyone's

00:29:53.527 --> 00:29:56.700
rising from the dead
before the resurrection

00:29:56.700 --> 00:29:58.280
at the end of the world.

00:29:58.280 --> 00:30:01.830
Nevertheless the original
disciples came to believe so

00:30:01.830 --> 00:30:05.180
strongly that God had
raised Jesus from the dead

00:30:05.180 --> 00:30:08.050
that they were willing
to die for the truth of

00:30:08.050 --> 00:30:09.340
that belief.

00:30:09.340 --> 00:30:11.240
N.T. Wright, an eminent New Testament

00:30:11.240 --> 00:30:14.967
scholar concludes, "That
is why as a historian

00:30:14.967 --> 00:30:18.107
"I cannot explain the
rise of early Christianity

00:30:18.107 --> 00:30:23.107
"unless Jesus rose again leaving
an empty tomb behind him."

00:30:23.160 --> 00:30:25.620
Attempts to explain away
these three great facts

00:30:25.620 --> 00:30:28.920
like the disciples stole the
body or Jesus wasn't really

00:30:28.920 --> 00:30:31.570
dead have been universally rejected by

00:30:31.570 --> 00:30:33.510
contemporary scholarship.

00:30:33.510 --> 00:30:36.800
The simple fact is that
there just is no plausible,

00:30:36.800 --> 00:30:40.490
naturalistic explanation of these facts.

00:30:40.490 --> 00:30:42.240
And therefore it seems to me the Christian

00:30:42.240 --> 00:30:45.310
is amply justified in believing that Jesus

00:30:45.310 --> 00:30:49.030
rose from the dead and
was who he claimed to be.

00:30:49.030 --> 00:30:52.023
But that entails that God exists.

00:30:53.380 --> 00:30:57.353
Finally, number five, the
immediate experience of God.

00:30:58.330 --> 00:31:00.960
This isn't really an
argument for God's existence,

00:31:00.960 --> 00:31:03.060
rather it's the claim
that you can know that

00:31:03.060 --> 00:31:05.010
God exists wholly apart from argument,

00:31:05.010 --> 00:31:08.280
simply by immediately experiencing him.

00:31:08.280 --> 00:31:10.207
Philosophers call beliefs like these

00:31:10.207 --> 00:31:12.530
"properly basic beliefs."

00:31:12.530 --> 00:31:14.670
They aren't based on other beliefs rather

00:31:14.670 --> 00:31:16.860
they're part of the
foundation of a person's

00:31:16.860 --> 00:31:18.340
system of beliefs.

00:31:18.340 --> 00:31:21.660
Other properly basic
beliefs include the belief

00:31:21.660 --> 00:31:24.018
in the reality of the external world,

00:31:24.018 --> 00:31:26.800
the belief in the existence of the past

00:31:26.800 --> 00:31:29.780
and the presence of other
minds like your own.

00:31:29.780 --> 00:31:33.290
When you think about it none
of these beliefs can be proved.

00:31:33.290 --> 00:31:35.520
But, although these sorts of beliefs

00:31:35.520 --> 00:31:38.910
are basic for us that doesn't
mean they're arbitrary.

00:31:38.910 --> 00:31:40.670
Rather they're grounded in the sense

00:31:40.670 --> 00:31:44.200
that they're formed in the
context of certain experiences.

00:31:44.200 --> 00:31:46.560
In the experiential context of seeing

00:31:46.560 --> 00:31:49.180
and hearing and feeling things I naturally

00:31:49.180 --> 00:31:52.460
form the belief in a
world of physical objects.

00:31:52.460 --> 00:31:55.030
And thus my beliefs are not arbitrary

00:31:55.030 --> 00:31:57.620
but appropriately grounded in experience.

00:31:57.620 --> 00:32:00.900
They're not merely basic
but properly basic.

00:32:00.900 --> 00:32:03.870
In the same way, belief in God is,

00:32:03.870 --> 00:32:07.750
for those who know him,
a properly basic belief

00:32:07.750 --> 00:32:11.410
grounded in our experience of God.

00:32:11.410 --> 00:32:14.130
Now, if this is right
there's a danger that

00:32:14.130 --> 00:32:16.500
arguments for God's
existence could actually

00:32:16.500 --> 00:32:19.720
distract your attention from God himself.

00:32:19.720 --> 00:32:22.610
If you're sincerely seeking God then

00:32:22.610 --> 00:32:25.620
God will make his
existence evident to you.

00:32:25.620 --> 00:32:28.619
We mustn't so concentrate
on the external arguments

00:32:28.619 --> 00:32:31.610
that we fail to hear
the inner voice of God

00:32:31.610 --> 00:32:33.560
speaking to our own hearts.

00:32:33.560 --> 00:32:35.760
For those who listen, God becomes

00:32:35.760 --> 00:32:39.310
an immediate reality in their lives.

00:32:39.310 --> 00:32:42.329
So, in conclusion then we've seen five

00:32:42.329 --> 00:32:45.860
good arguments to think that God exists.

00:32:45.860 --> 00:32:48.530
If Mr. Hitchens wants us
to believe instead that

00:32:48.530 --> 00:32:52.360
God does not exist, then
he must first tear down

00:32:52.360 --> 00:32:55.650
all five of the arguments
that I presented and

00:32:55.650 --> 00:32:58.320
then in their place
erect a case of his own

00:32:58.320 --> 00:33:00.830
to prove that God does not exist.

00:33:00.830 --> 00:33:05.090
Unless and until he does
that I think that theism

00:33:05.090 --> 00:33:07.303
is the more plausible world view.

