00:34:30.070 --> 00:34:33.200
Now, what I have discovered
in voyaging around

00:34:33.200 --> 00:34:35.390
this country and others in this debate

00:34:35.390 --> 00:34:39.390
and debating with Hindus,
with Muslims, with Jews,

00:34:39.390 --> 00:34:40.890
with Christians of all stripes,

00:34:40.890 --> 00:34:43.560
is that the arguments are all essentially

00:34:43.560 --> 00:34:46.230
the same for belief in the supernatural,

00:34:46.230 --> 00:34:49.160
for belief in faith, for belief in God,

00:34:49.160 --> 00:34:51.120
but that there are very interesting

00:34:51.120 --> 00:34:53.620
and noteworthy discrepancies between them.

00:34:53.620 --> 00:34:55.700
And one that I want to call attention

00:34:55.700 --> 00:34:57.810
to at the beginning of this evening

00:34:57.810 --> 00:35:00.970
is between those like
my friend Doug Wilson

00:35:00.970 --> 00:35:02.960
with whom I've now done a book of argument

00:35:02.960 --> 00:35:04.480
about Christian apologetics,

00:35:04.480 --> 00:35:06.490
who would call himself
a presuppositionalist,

00:35:06.490 --> 00:35:08.040
in other words, for whom really

00:35:08.040 --> 00:35:10.230
it's only necessary to
discover the workings

00:35:10.230 --> 00:35:14.790
of God's will in the cosmos and to assume

00:35:14.790 --> 00:35:18.640
that the truth of
Christianity is already proven

00:35:18.640 --> 00:35:21.230
and what are called,
they include Dr. Craig

00:35:21.230 --> 00:35:25.750
with great honor and respect
in this, the evidentialists.

00:35:25.750 --> 00:35:29.070
Now, I want to begin by
saying that this distinction

00:35:29.070 --> 00:35:31.890
strikes me first as a
very charming distinction

00:35:31.890 --> 00:35:35.220
and second as false, or
perhaps as a distinction

00:35:35.220 --> 00:35:36.600
without a difference.

00:35:36.600 --> 00:35:38.620
Well, why do I say charming?

00:35:38.620 --> 00:35:40.090
Because I think it's
rather sweet that people

00:35:40.090 --> 00:35:41.830
of faith also think
they ought to have some

00:35:41.830 --> 00:35:44.473
evidence and I think
it's progress of a kind.

00:35:45.350 --> 00:35:48.900
After all, if we had been
having this debate in the

00:35:48.900 --> 00:35:51.760
mid-19th century, Professor Craig or his

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:54.440
equivalent would have
known little or probably

00:35:54.440 --> 00:35:57.330
nothing about the laws
of physics and biology,

00:35:57.330 --> 00:35:59.360
maybe even less than I know now, which is,

00:35:59.360 --> 00:36:02.933
to say, quite a lot in it's way.

00:36:04.650 --> 00:36:05.920
And they would have grounded themselves,

00:36:05.920 --> 00:36:08.650
or he would have grounded
himself, on faith,

00:36:08.650 --> 00:36:12.230
on Scripture, on
revelation, on the prospect

00:36:12.230 --> 00:36:14.370
of salvation, on the means of grace,

00:36:14.370 --> 00:36:18.530
and the hope of glory
and perhaps on Paley's

00:36:18.530 --> 00:36:20.350
natural theology.

00:36:20.350 --> 00:36:22.200
Paley, who had the same
rooms, or had had the

00:36:22.200 --> 00:36:24.660
same rooms later occupied
by Charles Darwin

00:36:24.660 --> 00:36:27.040
in Cambridge with its watchmaker theory

00:36:27.040 --> 00:36:29.660
of design that I know
I don't have to expound

00:36:29.660 --> 00:36:31.740
to you but which briefly suggests that

00:36:31.740 --> 00:36:34.010
if an aborigine is walking along a beach

00:36:34.010 --> 00:36:38.130
and finds a gold watch
ticking he knows not

00:36:38.130 --> 00:36:40.510
what it's for or where it came from

00:36:40.510 --> 00:36:42.510
or who made it but he
knows it's not a rock,

00:36:42.510 --> 00:36:43.940
he knows it's not a vegetable, he knows it

00:36:43.940 --> 00:36:45.650
must have had a designer.

00:36:45.650 --> 00:36:48.062
The Paley analogy held for most Christians

00:36:48.062 --> 00:36:50.837
for many years because
they were willing to make

00:36:50.837 --> 00:36:53.910
the assumption that we
were mechanisms and that,

00:36:53.910 --> 00:36:56.680
therefore, there must be a watchmaker.

00:36:56.680 --> 00:36:59.391
But now that it's been, here's where the

00:36:59.391 --> 00:37:02.490
presuppositionalist-versus-evidentialist
dichotomy

00:37:02.490 --> 00:37:05.498
begins to kick in-now it's
been rather painstakingly

00:37:05.498 --> 00:37:09.230
and elaborately demonstrated
to the satisfaction

00:37:09.230 --> 00:37:11.670
of most people, I don't
want to just use arguments

00:37:11.670 --> 00:37:15.630
from authority, but it's not
very much contested any more,

00:37:15.630 --> 00:37:18.780
that we are not designed as creatures,

00:37:18.780 --> 00:37:22.910
but that we evolved by a
rather laborious combination

00:37:22.910 --> 00:37:25.680
of random mutation and natural selection

00:37:25.680 --> 00:37:28.563
into the species that we are today.

00:37:29.469 --> 00:37:31.130
It is, of course, open to the faithful

00:37:31.130 --> 00:37:35.060
to say that all this was, now
that they come to know it,

00:37:35.060 --> 00:37:37.330
now that it becomes
available to everybody,

00:37:37.330 --> 00:37:39.300
now that they think about it,

00:37:39.300 --> 00:37:43.330
and now that they've stopped
opposing it or trying ban it,

00:37:43.330 --> 00:37:46.237
then they can say, "Ah,
actually, on second thought

00:37:46.237 --> 00:37:49.010
"the evolution was all
part of the design."

00:37:49.010 --> 00:37:51.060
Well, as you will recognize,
ladies and gentlemen,

00:37:51.060 --> 00:37:52.830
there are some arguments
I can't be expected

00:37:52.830 --> 00:37:55.860
to refute or rebut because there's no way

00:37:55.860 --> 00:37:56.980
around that argument.

00:37:56.980 --> 00:37:59.290
I mean, if everything,
including evolution,

00:37:59.290 --> 00:38:02.260
which isn't a design, is nonetheless part

00:38:02.260 --> 00:38:04.320
of a divine design than all the advantage

00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:06.130
goes to the person who's
willing to believe that.

00:38:06.130 --> 00:38:08.770
That cannot be disproved
but it does seem to

00:38:08.770 --> 00:38:10.780
be a very poor, very weak argument because

00:38:10.780 --> 00:38:13.360
the test of a good argument is that it is

00:38:13.360 --> 00:38:16.190
falsifiable not that it's unfalsifiable.

00:38:16.190 --> 00:38:19.700
So this I would therefore, this tactic,

00:38:19.700 --> 00:38:22.230
or this style of argument, which we've had

00:38:22.230 --> 00:38:24.607
some evidence of this
evening, I would rebaptize

00:38:24.607 --> 00:38:27.140
or when I dare say rechristen

00:38:27.140 --> 00:38:30.450
it as retrospective evidentialism.

00:38:30.450 --> 00:38:31.900
In other words everything can,

00:38:31.900 --> 00:38:36.030
in due time, if you have
enough faith, be made to fit.

00:38:36.030 --> 00:38:38.621
And you too are all quite free to believe

00:38:38.621 --> 00:38:42.290
that a sentient creator deliberately,

00:38:42.290 --> 00:38:44.420
consciously put himself, a being,

00:38:44.420 --> 00:38:47.670
put himself or herself
or itself to the trouble

00:38:47.670 --> 00:38:50.989
of going through huge epochs of birth

00:38:50.989 --> 00:38:55.989
and death of species over
eons of time in which 99%,

00:38:57.500 --> 00:39:02.500
in the course of which at
least 99.9% of all species,

00:39:03.210 --> 00:39:05.905
all life forms, ever to
have appeared on earth have

00:39:05.905 --> 00:39:10.310
become extinct, as we nearly
did as a species ourselves.

00:39:10.310 --> 00:39:12.870
I invite you to look up the
very alarming and beautiful

00:39:12.870 --> 00:39:16.240
and brilliant account by
the National Geographic's

00:39:16.240 --> 00:39:18.100
coordinator of the genome project.

00:39:18.100 --> 00:39:20.470
By the way you should
send in your little sample

00:39:20.470 --> 00:39:22.670
from the inside of you cheek and have your

00:39:22.670 --> 00:39:24.010
African ancestry traced.

00:39:24.010 --> 00:39:26.350
It's absolutely fascinating to follow

00:39:26.350 --> 00:39:28.970
the mitochondrial DNA
that we all have in common

00:39:28.970 --> 00:39:31.110
and that we have in
common with other species,

00:39:31.110 --> 00:39:33.260
other primates, and other life forms

00:39:33.260 --> 00:39:34.910
and find out where in
Africa you came from.

00:39:34.910 --> 00:39:37.600
But there came a time, probably about

00:39:37.600 --> 00:39:41.130
180,000 years ago, when, due to a terrible

00:39:41.130 --> 00:39:43.790
climatic event, probably in Indonesia,

00:39:43.790 --> 00:39:46.610
an appalling global
warming crisis occurred

00:39:46.610 --> 00:39:48.790
and the estimate is that
the number of humans

00:39:48.790 --> 00:39:51.923
in Africa went down to
between 40 and 30,000.

00:39:52.950 --> 00:39:56.450
This close, this close,
think about fine tuning.

00:39:56.450 --> 00:39:58.460
This close to joining every other species

00:39:58.460 --> 00:40:00.130
that had gone extinct.

00:40:00.130 --> 00:40:02.250
And that's our Exodus
story is that somehow

00:40:02.250 --> 00:40:04.400
we don't know how because it's
not written in any Scripture,

00:40:04.400 --> 00:40:06.060
it's not told in any book, it's not part

00:40:06.060 --> 00:40:08.530
of any superstitious narrative
but somehow we escaped

00:40:08.530 --> 00:40:11.280
from Africa to cooler latitudes was made,

00:40:11.280 --> 00:40:12.250
but that's how close it was.

00:40:12.250 --> 00:40:14.135
You have to be able to
imagine that all this

00:40:14.135 --> 00:40:17.460
mass extinction and death and randomness

00:40:17.460 --> 00:40:19.146
is the will of a being.

00:40:19.146 --> 00:40:24.146
You are absolutely free to
believe that if you wish.

00:40:24.670 --> 00:40:27.040
And all of this should happen so that

00:40:27.040 --> 00:40:30.980
one very imperfect race
of evolved primates

00:40:30.980 --> 00:40:32.820
should have the opportunity
to become Christians

00:40:32.820 --> 00:40:35.935
or to turn up at this
gym tonight, that all of

00:40:35.935 --> 00:40:38.780
that was done with us in view.

00:40:38.780 --> 00:40:41.590
It's a curious kind of solipsism,

00:40:41.590 --> 00:40:43.270
it's a curious kind of self-centeredness.

00:40:43.270 --> 00:40:44.420
I was always brought up to believe that

00:40:44.420 --> 00:40:46.750
Christians were modest and humble,

00:40:46.750 --> 00:40:49.400
they comported themselves
with due humility.

00:40:49.400 --> 00:40:51.010
This, there's a certain arrogance to this

00:40:51.010 --> 00:40:53.486
assumption all of this,
all of this extraordinary

00:40:53.486 --> 00:40:57.020
development was all about us and we were

00:40:57.020 --> 00:40:58.560
the intended and the desired result

00:40:58.560 --> 00:41:00.640
and everything else was in the discard.

00:41:00.640 --> 00:41:02.490
The tremendous wastefulness of it,

00:41:02.490 --> 00:41:06.190
the tremendous cruelty of it,
the tremendous caprice of it,

00:41:06.190 --> 00:41:08.420
the tremendous tinkering
and incompetence of it,

00:41:08.420 --> 00:41:11.330
never mind at least we're here and we can

00:41:11.330 --> 00:41:12.570
be people of faith.

00:41:12.570 --> 00:41:15.120
It doesn't work me, I
have to simply say that

00:41:15.120 --> 00:41:17.320
and I think there may be
questions of psychology

00:41:17.320 --> 00:41:19.663
involved in this as well.

00:41:20.670 --> 00:41:23.740
Believe it if you can, I can't stop you.

00:41:23.740 --> 00:41:25.690
Believe it if you like, you're welcome.

00:41:25.690 --> 00:41:27.540
It's obviously impossible,
as I said before,

00:41:27.540 --> 00:41:30.300
to disprove and it equally
obviously helps you

00:41:30.300 --> 00:41:33.010
to believe it if, as we all are,

00:41:33.010 --> 00:41:34.890
you're in the happy position
of knowing the outcome,

00:41:34.890 --> 00:41:36.880
in other words we are here.

00:41:36.880 --> 00:41:39.410
But there's a fallacy lurking
in there somewhere too,

00:41:39.410 --> 00:41:41.120
is there not?

00:41:41.120 --> 00:41:43.170
Now it's often said, it was said tonight,

00:41:44.340 --> 00:41:45.823
and Dr. Craig said it in print,

00:41:45.823 --> 00:41:49.790
that atheists think they can
prove the nonexistence of God.

00:41:49.790 --> 00:41:52.688
This, in fact, very slightly
but crucially misrepresents

00:41:52.688 --> 00:41:55.000
what we've always said.

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:56.550
There's nothing new
about the New Atheists,

00:41:56.550 --> 00:41:59.060
it's just we're recent,
there's nothing particularly,

00:41:59.060 --> 00:42:01.770
Dr. Victor Stenger, a great scientist,

00:42:01.770 --> 00:42:04.550
has written a book called
The Failed Hypothesis,

00:42:04.550 --> 00:42:06.080
which he says he thinks that science

00:42:06.080 --> 00:42:11.080
can now license the claim that
there definitely is no God,

00:42:11.220 --> 00:42:13.040
but he's unique in that, and I think

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:14.170
very bold and courageous.

00:42:14.170 --> 00:42:15.243
Here's what we argue.

00:42:17.470 --> 00:42:18.380
We argue quite simply

00:42:18.380 --> 00:42:21.670
that there's no plausible
or convincing reason,

00:42:21.670 --> 00:42:24.017
certainly no evidential one, to believe

00:42:24.017 --> 00:42:26.980
that there is such an entity, and that all

00:42:26.980 --> 00:42:29.120
observable phenomena,
including the cosmological

00:42:29.120 --> 00:42:32.710
one to which I'm coming, are explicable

00:42:32.710 --> 00:42:33.830
without the hypothesis.

00:42:33.830 --> 00:42:35.330
You don't need the assumption.

00:42:36.500 --> 00:42:39.270
And this objection
itself, our school falls

00:42:39.270 --> 00:42:42.170
into at least two, perhaps three sections.

00:42:42.170 --> 00:42:44.160
There's no such thing, no such word though

00:42:44.160 --> 00:42:48.260
there should be, as "adeism"
or as being an "adeist"

00:42:48.260 --> 00:42:51.060
but there if was one I
would say that's what I was.

00:42:51.060 --> 00:42:53.630
I don't believe that we
are here as the result

00:42:53.630 --> 00:42:55.940
of a design or that by making the

00:42:55.940 --> 00:42:58.010
appropriate propitiations and adopting

00:42:58.010 --> 00:43:00.370
the appropriate postures and following

00:43:00.370 --> 00:43:02.600
the appropriate rituals we can overcome

00:43:02.600 --> 00:43:05.820
death I don't believe that and for

00:43:05.820 --> 00:43:08.740
a priori of reasons don't.

00:43:08.740 --> 00:43:10.060
If there was such a force,

00:43:10.060 --> 00:43:13.830
which I cannot prove by
definition that there was not,

00:43:13.830 --> 00:43:15.800
if there was an entity
that was responsible

00:43:15.800 --> 00:43:17.930
for the beginning of the cosmos, and that

00:43:17.930 --> 00:43:20.730
also happened to be busily engineering

00:43:20.730 --> 00:43:23.040
the very laborious product,
production of life on

00:43:23.040 --> 00:43:26.110
our little planet, it
still wouldn't prove that

00:43:26.110 --> 00:43:31.110
this entity cared about
us, answered prayers,

00:43:31.370 --> 00:43:33.500
cared what church we went to, or whether

00:43:33.500 --> 00:43:35.630
we went to one at all,
cared who we had sex

00:43:35.630 --> 00:43:37.950
with or in what position or by what means,

00:43:37.950 --> 00:43:40.420
cared what we ate or on what day,

00:43:40.420 --> 00:43:41.690
cared whether we lived or died.

00:43:41.690 --> 00:43:43.140
There's no reason at all why this

00:43:43.140 --> 00:43:45.253
entity isn't completely indifferent to us.

00:43:45.253 --> 00:43:48.930
That you cannot get from deism to theism

00:43:48.930 --> 00:43:52.360
except by a series of
extraordinarily generous,

00:43:52.360 --> 00:43:54.640
to yourself, assumptions.

00:43:54.640 --> 00:43:57.270
The deist has all his work still ahead of

00:43:57.270 --> 00:44:00.210
him to show that it leads to revelation,

00:44:00.210 --> 00:44:03.760
to redemption, to
salvation or to suspensions

00:44:03.760 --> 00:44:05.170
of the natural order in which hitherto

00:44:05.170 --> 00:44:06.880
you'd be putting all of your faith,

00:44:06.880 --> 00:44:10.852
all your evidence is on scientific
and natural evidence or,

00:44:10.852 --> 00:44:12.990
why not, for a change of pace for a change

00:44:12.990 --> 00:44:14.927
of taste say, "Yes, but sometimes this

00:44:14.927 --> 00:44:18.757
"same natural order, which is
so miraculous in observation,

00:44:18.757 --> 00:44:22.367
"no question about it, is so
impressive in its favoring

00:44:22.367 --> 00:44:24.707
"the conditions for life in some ways,

00:44:24.707 --> 00:44:28.440
"but its randomly suspended
when miracles are required."

00:44:28.440 --> 00:44:31.010
So with caprice and
contempt these laws turn

00:44:31.010 --> 00:44:33.510
out to be not so important after all

00:44:33.510 --> 00:44:34.620
as long as the truth of religion

00:44:34.620 --> 00:44:36.950
can be proved by their
being rendered inoperative.

00:44:36.950 --> 00:44:38.186
This is having it both ways

00:44:38.186 --> 00:44:41.290
in the most promiscuous
and exorbitant manner,

00:44:41.290 --> 00:44:43.153
in my submission.

00:44:44.810 --> 00:44:46.610
Bear in mind also that these are not

00:44:46.610 --> 00:44:49.300
precisely the differences,
between Dr. Craig

00:44:49.300 --> 00:44:51.410
and myself I mean,
morally or intellectually

00:44:51.410 --> 00:44:52.243
equivalent claims.

00:44:52.243 --> 00:44:55.130
After all, Dr. Craig,
to win this argument,

00:44:55.130 --> 00:44:58.460
has to believe and prove to certainty.

00:44:58.460 --> 00:44:59.840
He's not just saying there might be a

00:44:59.840 --> 00:45:02.650
God because he has to say that there must

00:45:02.650 --> 00:45:04.018
be one otherwise we couldn't be here

00:45:04.018 --> 00:45:06.210
and there couldn't be morality.

00:45:06.210 --> 00:45:08.490
It's not a contingency for him.

00:45:08.490 --> 00:45:12.690
I have to say that I appear as a skeptic

00:45:12.690 --> 00:45:16.010
who believes that doubt
is the great engine,

00:45:16.010 --> 00:45:19.950
the great fuel of all
inquiry, all discovery,

00:45:19.950 --> 00:45:23.600
and all innovation and
that I doubt these things.

00:45:23.600 --> 00:45:25.528
The disadvantage, it seems to me,

00:45:25.528 --> 00:45:27.387
in the argument goes
to the person who says,

00:45:27.387 --> 00:45:30.750
"No, I know, I know it it
must be true, it is true."

00:45:30.750 --> 00:45:33.290
We're too early in the study
of physics and biology,

00:45:33.290 --> 00:45:35.240
it seems to me, to be
dealing in certainties

00:45:35.240 --> 00:45:37.370
of that kind especially
when the stakes are so high.

00:45:37.370 --> 00:45:40.060
It seems to me, to put
it in a condensed form,

00:45:40.060 --> 00:45:42.014
extraordinary claims,
such as the existence

00:45:42.014 --> 00:45:45.930
of a divine power with
a son who cares enough

00:45:45.930 --> 00:45:47.680
to come and redeem us, extraordinary

00:45:47.680 --> 00:45:50.120
claims require truly
extraordinary evidence.

00:45:50.120 --> 00:45:52.840
I don't think any of the
evidence we heard from Dr. Craig,

00:45:52.840 --> 00:45:54.730
brilliantly marshaled as it was,

00:45:54.730 --> 00:45:58.960
was extraordinary enough
to justify the extreme

00:45:58.960 --> 00:46:01.813
claims that are being made, backed by it.

00:46:03.140 --> 00:46:05.777
"Hypocrisy," said La Rochefoucauld,

00:46:05.777 --> 00:46:08.397
"Is the compliment that
vice pays to virtue."

00:46:09.400 --> 00:46:11.470
Retrospective evidentialism strikes me

00:46:11.470 --> 00:46:13.060
in something of the same sort of light.

00:46:13.060 --> 00:46:18.060
It's a concession made
to the need for fact.

00:46:19.130 --> 00:46:21.540
Maybe we better have some
evidence to along with our faith.

00:46:21.540 --> 00:46:24.360
But look what Dr. Craig says in his book.

00:46:24.360 --> 00:46:26.647
He says, I'll quote directly, he says,

00:46:26.647 --> 00:46:29.687
"Should a conflict arise between

00:46:29.687 --> 00:46:31.347
"the witness of the Holy Spirit to

00:46:31.347 --> 00:46:33.727
"the fundamental truth
of the Christian faith

00:46:33.727 --> 00:46:36.357
"and beliefs based on
argument and evidence

00:46:36.357 --> 00:46:38.357
"then it is the former
which must take precedence

00:46:38.357 --> 00:46:39.930
"over the latter."

00:46:39.930 --> 00:46:42.500
He adds not vice-versa
but a good editor would've

00:46:42.500 --> 00:46:45.180
told you you don't have
to put the vice-versa in,

00:46:45.180 --> 00:46:46.450
it's clear enough as it is.

00:46:46.450 --> 00:46:48.597
I'll say it again,
"Should a conflict arise

00:46:48.597 --> 00:46:50.347
"between the witness of the Holy Spirit

00:46:50.347 --> 00:46:52.457
"to the fundamental truth
of the Christian faith

00:46:52.457 --> 00:46:54.097
"and beliefs based on
argument and evidence

00:46:54.097 --> 00:46:55.947
"then it is the former which must take

00:46:55.947 --> 00:46:57.490
"precedence over the latter."

00:46:57.490 --> 00:47:01.170
That's not evidentialism,
that's just faith.

00:47:01.170 --> 00:47:03.293
It's a priori belief.

00:47:05.210 --> 00:47:07.230
It's rephrased in another edition.

00:47:07.230 --> 00:47:08.597
It says, "Therefore the role of rational

00:47:08.597 --> 00:47:11.267
"argumentation in knowing Christianity

00:47:11.267 --> 00:47:13.747
"to be true is the role of a servant.

00:47:13.747 --> 00:47:15.387
"A person knows Christianity is true

00:47:15.387 --> 00:47:18.557
"because the Holy Spirit
tells him it is true.

00:47:18.557 --> 00:47:20.057
"And while argument and evidence can be

00:47:20.057 --> 00:47:21.177
"used to support this conclusion

00:47:21.177 --> 00:47:23.387
"they cannot legitimately overrule it."

00:47:25.210 --> 00:47:27.910
Now, then he goes on to say the Bible says

00:47:27.910 --> 00:47:28.987
all men are without excuse.

00:47:28.987 --> 00:47:31.647
"Even those who are given
no reason to believe,

00:47:31.647 --> 00:47:33.307
"and many persuasive
reasons to disbelieve,

00:47:33.307 --> 00:47:35.677
"have no excuse but
because the ultimate reason

00:47:35.677 --> 00:47:37.207
"they do not believe is that they have

00:47:37.207 --> 00:47:39.070
"deliberately rejected God's Holy Spirit."

00:47:39.070 --> 00:47:40.670
That would have to be me.

00:47:40.670 --> 00:47:42.650
But you see where this lands
you, ladies and gentlemen,

00:47:42.650 --> 00:47:44.730
with the Christian apologetic.

00:47:44.730 --> 00:47:46.520
You're told you're a miserable sinner,

00:47:46.520 --> 00:47:48.860
who is without excuse;

00:47:48.860 --> 00:47:51.541
you've disappointed your God who made you

00:47:51.541 --> 00:47:54.700
and you've been so ungrateful as to rebel;

00:47:54.700 --> 00:47:56.627
you're contemptible; you're worm-like;

00:47:56.627 --> 00:47:59.240
but you can take heart, the whole universe

00:47:59.240 --> 00:48:00.990
was designed with just you in mind.

00:48:01.950 --> 00:48:05.350
These two claims are not
just mutually exclusive

00:48:05.350 --> 00:48:07.100
but I think they're intended to compensate

00:48:07.100 --> 00:48:10.653
each other's cruelty and,
ultimately, absurdity.

00:48:12.730 --> 00:48:14.807
In other words, evidence is
an occasional convenience.

00:48:14.807 --> 00:48:15.640
"Seek and ye shall find."

00:48:15.640 --> 00:48:17.670
I remember being told that in church

00:48:17.670 --> 00:48:19.437
many a time as a young lad.

00:48:19.437 --> 00:48:20.370
"Seek and ye shall find."

00:48:20.370 --> 00:48:22.500
I thought it was a sinister injunction

00:48:22.500 --> 00:48:24.060
because it's all too likely to be true.

00:48:24.060 --> 00:48:26.900
We are pattern-seeking
mammals and primates.

00:48:26.900 --> 00:48:30.440
If we can't get good evidence
we'll go for junk evidence.

00:48:30.440 --> 00:48:31.730
If we can't get a real theory

00:48:31.730 --> 00:48:33.270
we'll go with a conspiracy theory.

00:48:33.270 --> 00:48:34.610
You see it all the time.

00:48:34.610 --> 00:48:36.651
Religion's great strength
is that it was the first

00:48:36.651 --> 00:48:39.470
of our attempts to explain reality,

00:48:39.470 --> 00:48:41.910
to make those patterns
take some kind of form.

00:48:41.910 --> 00:48:42.770
It deserves credit.

00:48:42.770 --> 00:48:44.860
It was our first attempt at astronomy;

00:48:44.860 --> 00:48:46.250
our first attempt at cosmology;

00:48:46.250 --> 00:48:48.520
in some ways our first
attempt at medicine;

00:48:48.520 --> 00:48:50.220
our first attempt at literature;

00:48:50.220 --> 00:48:51.730
our first attempt at philosophy.

00:48:51.730 --> 00:48:54.410
Good, while there was nothing else,

00:48:54.410 --> 00:48:57.160
it had many functional uses of mankind.

00:48:57.160 --> 00:48:58.920
Never mind that they didn't know

00:48:58.920 --> 00:49:00.950
that germs caused disease,
maybe evil spirits

00:49:00.950 --> 00:49:03.640
caused disease, maybe
disease is a punishment;

00:49:03.640 --> 00:49:05.900
never mind that they believed in astrology

00:49:05.900 --> 00:49:07.390
rather than astronomy.

00:49:07.390 --> 00:49:09.330
Even Thomas Aquinas believed in astrology.

00:49:09.330 --> 00:49:11.630
Never mind that they believed in devils;

00:49:11.630 --> 00:49:14.690
never mind that things
like volcanic eruptions,

00:49:14.690 --> 00:49:17.610
earthquakes, tidal waves were
thought of as punishments,

00:49:17.610 --> 00:49:22.523
not as natural occurrences on
the cooling crust of a planet.

00:49:25.130 --> 00:49:27.500
The pattern seeking has gone too far

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:32.810
and it's gone, I think, much too far with

00:49:32.810 --> 00:49:34.500
what was until recently thought of as

00:49:34.500 --> 00:49:37.950
Christianity's greatest failure,
greatest of all failures:

00:49:37.950 --> 00:49:39.770
cosmology, the one thing Christianity

00:49:39.770 --> 00:49:41.750
knew nothing about and taught the

00:49:41.750 --> 00:49:43.223
most abject nonsense about.

00:49:44.176 --> 00:49:45.740
For most of its lifetime Christianity

00:49:45.740 --> 00:49:47.810
taught that the earth
itself was the center

00:49:47.810 --> 00:49:50.150
of the universe and we had been given

00:49:50.150 --> 00:49:52.550
exclusive dominion as a species over it.

00:49:52.550 --> 00:49:54.590
Could not have been more wrong.

00:49:54.590 --> 00:49:56.570
How are we going to
square the new cosmology,

00:49:56.570 --> 00:49:58.760
the fantastic new discoveries in physics

00:49:58.760 --> 00:49:59.970
with the old dogmas?

00:49:59.970 --> 00:50:02.888
Well, one is the idea of this fine tuning

00:50:02.888 --> 00:50:06.350
about which I've only left
myself three and a half minutes.

00:50:06.350 --> 00:50:09.343
I'll have to refer some of this
to later in the discussion.

00:50:11.310 --> 00:50:13.380
This is essentially another
form of pattern seeking

00:50:13.380 --> 00:50:16.070
on the basis of extremely
limited evidence.

00:50:16.070 --> 00:50:19.170
Most physicists are very uncertain,

00:50:19.170 --> 00:50:20.950
as they have every right to be.

00:50:20.950 --> 00:50:23.380
In fact, I would say for physicists

00:50:23.380 --> 00:50:25.750
as they have the duty
to be, at the moment,

00:50:25.750 --> 00:50:28.930
extremely uncertain
about the spatio-temporal

00:50:28.930 --> 00:50:31.070
dimensions of the original episode,

00:50:31.070 --> 00:50:32.895
the Big Bang at it's sometimes called.

00:50:32.895 --> 00:50:35.073
We're in the very, very early stages

00:50:35.073 --> 00:50:36.080
of this inquiry.

00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:39.180
We hardly know what we
don't know about the origins

00:50:39.180 --> 00:50:40.013
of the universe.

00:50:41.360 --> 00:50:43.550
We're viewing it from an
unimaginable distance,

00:50:43.550 --> 00:50:46.220
not just an unimaginable
distance in space,

00:50:46.220 --> 00:50:47.892
perched on a tiny rock on an extremely

00:50:47.892 --> 00:50:51.470
small suburb of a fairly minor galaxy,

00:50:51.470 --> 00:50:53.740
trying to look, to discern our origins,

00:50:53.740 --> 00:50:56.040
but also at a very unbelievable distance

00:50:56.040 --> 00:50:57.817
in time and we claim the right to say,

00:50:57.817 --> 00:51:01.180
"Ah, we can see the finger
of God in this process."

00:51:01.180 --> 00:51:04.570
It's an extraordinarily
arrogant assumption.

00:51:04.570 --> 00:51:06.980
It either deserves a
Nobel Prize in physics,

00:51:06.980 --> 00:51:08.970
which it hasn't yet got, I notice.

00:51:08.970 --> 00:51:10.450
I don't know any physicists who believes

00:51:10.450 --> 00:51:12.390
these assumptions are necessary.

00:51:12.390 --> 00:51:16.469
Or it deserves a charge of hubris.

00:51:16.469 --> 00:51:19.290
Let me make three tiny quick objections to

00:51:19.290 --> 00:51:21.430
it as it stands, and
I'm no more a physicist

00:51:21.430 --> 00:51:22.493
than most of you are.

00:51:23.720 --> 00:51:24.920
I'll make these lay objections.

00:51:24.920 --> 00:51:28.170
One, was there pre-existing material

00:51:28.170 --> 00:51:31.713
for this extra-spatio-temporal
being to work with,

00:51:32.690 --> 00:51:36.540
or did he just will it into
existence, the ex nihilo?

00:51:36.540 --> 00:51:38.630
Who designed the designer?

00:51:38.630 --> 00:51:40.960
Don't you run the risk
with the presumption

00:51:40.960 --> 00:51:43.977
of a god and a designer and
an originator of asking,

00:51:43.977 --> 00:51:45.727
"Well, where does that come from,

00:51:45.727 --> 00:51:46.780
"where does that come from,"

00:51:46.780 --> 00:51:50.040
and locking yourself
into an infinite regress?

00:51:50.040 --> 00:51:52.730
Why are there so many shooting stars,

00:51:52.730 --> 00:51:55.900
collapsed suns, failed
galaxies we can see?

00:51:55.900 --> 00:51:57.190
We can see with the aid of a telescope,

00:51:57.190 --> 00:52:00.650
some we can see with the
naked eye the utter failure,

00:52:00.650 --> 00:52:03.910
the total destruction
of gigantic unimaginable

00:52:03.910 --> 00:52:05.940
sweeps of outer space.

00:52:05.940 --> 00:52:09.400
Is this fine tuning, or
is it extremely random,

00:52:09.400 --> 00:52:13.543
capricious, cruel,
mysterious, and incompetent?

00:52:15.170 --> 00:52:20.170
And, have you thought of the
nothingness that's coming?

00:52:20.290 --> 00:52:22.650
We know we have something now,

00:52:22.650 --> 00:52:25.410
and we speculate about what
it might have come from

00:52:25.410 --> 00:52:26.650
and there's a real question about

00:52:26.650 --> 00:52:30.780
ex nihilo, but nihilo is coming to us.

00:52:30.780 --> 00:52:32.070
In the night sky you can already see

00:52:32.070 --> 00:52:33.730
the Andromeda galaxy,
it's heading straight

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:35.340
for ours on a collision course.

00:52:35.340 --> 00:52:36.600
Is that part of a design?

00:52:36.600 --> 00:52:38.683
Was it fine tuned to do that?

00:52:39.580 --> 00:52:41.880
We know that from the red light shift

00:52:41.880 --> 00:52:43.150
of the Hubble telescope, or rather

00:52:43.150 --> 00:52:44.930
Edwin Hubble's original discovery,

00:52:44.930 --> 00:52:46.970
the universe is expanding away from itself

00:52:46.970 --> 00:52:48.650
at a tremendous rate.

00:52:48.650 --> 00:52:49.850
It was thought that rate would go

00:52:49.850 --> 00:52:52.000
down for Newtonian reasons.

00:52:52.000 --> 00:52:54.770
No, it's recently been proved
by Professor Lawrence Krauss

00:52:54.770 --> 00:52:57.070
the rate of expansion is increasing.

00:52:57.070 --> 00:53:00.110
Everything's exploding away even faster.

00:53:00.110 --> 00:53:01.730
Nothingness is certainly coming.

00:53:01.730 --> 00:53:04.183
Who designed that?

00:53:05.580 --> 00:53:08.730
That's all if before these things happen

00:53:08.730 --> 00:53:11.010
we don't have the destruction of our own

00:53:11.010 --> 00:53:14.230
little solar system in which already

00:53:14.230 --> 00:53:15.800
there's only one planet where anything

00:53:15.800 --> 00:53:17.440
like life can possibly be supported.

00:53:17.440 --> 00:53:20.770
All the other planets
are too hot or too cold

00:53:20.770 --> 00:53:23.190
to support any life at
all and the sun is due

00:53:23.190 --> 00:53:26.700
to swell up, burn us to
a crisp, boil our oceans,

00:53:26.700 --> 00:53:28.720
and die as we've seen all the other suns

00:53:28.720 --> 00:53:30.040
do in the night sky.

00:53:30.040 --> 00:53:31.850
This is not fine tuning,
ladies and gentlemen,

00:53:31.850 --> 00:53:33.782
and if it's the work of a designer,

00:53:33.782 --> 00:53:35.990
then there's an indictment to which

00:53:35.990 --> 00:53:38.720
that designer may have to be subjected.

00:53:38.720 --> 00:53:40.120
I'm out of time, I'm very grateful

00:53:40.120 --> 00:53:41.564
for your kindness and hospitality.

00:53:41.564 --> 00:53:46.564
Thank you.
[audience applause]

00:53:56.520 --> 00:53:59.427
&gt;&gt; Dr. Craig, a 12 minute rebuttal.

00:54:11.130 --> 00:54:12.950
&gt;&gt; You'll remember that
in my opening speech,

00:54:12.950 --> 00:54:15.560
I said I would defend
two basic contentions

00:54:15.560 --> 00:54:17.240
in tonight's debate.

00:54:17.240 --> 00:54:21.160
First, that there's no good
argument that atheism is true.

00:54:21.160 --> 00:54:24.210
Now, far from being a point
of contention tonight,

00:54:24.210 --> 00:54:27.120
as far as I understood
Mr. Hitchens' last speech,

00:54:27.120 --> 00:54:29.270
he would agree with that first statement

00:54:29.270 --> 00:54:32.680
that there is no good
argument that atheism is true.

00:54:32.680 --> 00:54:35.657
He says, "I simply don't
have any positive reason

00:54:35.657 --> 00:54:37.390
"to believe in God."

00:54:37.390 --> 00:54:39.950
But he doesn't really
give an argument against

00:54:39.950 --> 00:54:40.783
God's existence.

00:54:40.783 --> 00:54:43.560
Indeed, he seems to
suggest that's impossible.

00:54:43.560 --> 00:54:45.540
But notice that doesn't prove atheism.

00:54:45.540 --> 00:54:48.120
That just leaves you
with agnosticism, mainly,

00:54:48.120 --> 00:54:51.600
you don't know if there's
a God or no, so, at best,

00:54:51.600 --> 00:54:53.770
you're left merely with agnosticism.

00:54:53.770 --> 00:54:56.090
We don't see any good reason to think that

00:54:56.090 --> 00:54:57.670
atheism is true.

00:54:57.670 --> 00:55:00.660
Now he did makes some remarks
about the theory of evolution

00:55:00.660 --> 00:55:03.570
which at least insinuated
that this was somehow

00:55:03.570 --> 00:55:05.740
incompatible with theism, and I have

00:55:05.740 --> 00:55:07.140
two points to make about this.

00:55:07.140 --> 00:55:09.250
First, I think that the
theory of biological

00:55:09.250 --> 00:55:12.160
evolution is simply
irrelevant to the truth

00:55:12.160 --> 00:55:13.920
of Christian theism.

00:55:13.920 --> 00:55:16.380
Genesis, one, admits
all manner of different

00:55:16.380 --> 00:55:18.910
interpretations and one is by no means

00:55:18.910 --> 00:55:21.430
committed to six-day creationism.

00:55:21.430 --> 00:55:23.400
Howard van Till, who is a professor

00:55:23.400 --> 00:55:26.487
at Calvin College,
writes, "Is the concept of

00:55:26.487 --> 00:55:29.257
"special creation required of all persons

00:55:29.257 --> 00:55:31.787
"who trust in the
creator God of Scripture?

00:55:31.787 --> 00:55:33.357
"Most Christians in my acquaintance

00:55:33.357 --> 00:55:35.177
"who are engaged with either scientific

00:55:35.177 --> 00:55:37.557
"or biblical scholarship have concluded

00:55:37.557 --> 00:55:39.397
"that the special creationists' picture of

00:55:39.397 --> 00:55:42.937
"the world's formation is
not a necessary component

00:55:42.937 --> 00:55:45.877
"of Christian belief,
nor is this a retreat

00:55:45.877 --> 00:55:47.980
"caused by modern science."

00:55:47.980 --> 00:55:50.300
Saint Augustin in the AD 300s,

00:55:50.300 --> 00:55:52.396
in his commentary on Genesis,

00:55:52.396 --> 00:55:54.850
pointed out that the days
don't need to be taken

00:55:54.850 --> 00:55:59.080
literally nor need the creation
be a few thousand years ago.

00:55:59.080 --> 00:56:00.956
Indeed he suggested
that God made the world

00:56:00.956 --> 00:56:03.140
with certain special potencies that would

00:56:03.140 --> 00:56:06.377
gradually unfold over time and develop.

00:56:06.377 --> 00:56:11.270
This interpretation came 1500 years before

00:56:11.270 --> 00:56:15.320
Darwin so that it is not a forced retreat

00:56:15.320 --> 00:56:17.400
in the face of modern science.

00:56:17.400 --> 00:56:19.370
So any doubts that I would have about

00:56:19.370 --> 00:56:21.480
the theory of biological evolution would

00:56:21.480 --> 00:56:25.390
be not biblical but rather scientific,

00:56:25.390 --> 00:56:30.260
namely, what it imagines is
fantastically improbable.

00:56:30.260 --> 00:56:32.264
Barrow and Tipler, two
physicists in their book

00:56:32.264 --> 00:56:35.510
The Anthropic Cosmological Principle

00:56:35.510 --> 00:56:39.033
list ten steps in the
course of human evolution,

00:56:39.033 --> 00:56:41.805
each of which is so improbable that before

00:56:41.805 --> 00:56:44.660
it would occur the sun would have ceased

00:56:44.660 --> 00:56:48.950
to be a main sequence star
and incinerated the earth.

00:56:48.950 --> 00:56:52.115
And they calculate the
probability of the evolution

00:56:52.115 --> 00:56:54.910
of the human genome to
be somewhere between

00:56:54.910 --> 00:56:59.910
four to the negative 180th
power to the 110,000th power

00:57:01.490 --> 00:57:06.490
and four to the negative 360th
power to the 110,000th power.

00:57:06.970 --> 00:57:10.190
So, if evolution did occur on this planet

00:57:10.190 --> 00:57:13.040
it was literally a miracle,
and therefore evidence

00:57:13.040 --> 00:57:16.720
for the existence of God.
[audience applause]

00:57:16.720 --> 00:57:20.030
So I don't think this is
an argument for atheism,

00:57:20.030 --> 00:57:22.022
quite the contrary, it
really provides good grounds

00:57:22.022 --> 00:57:24.350
for thinking that God superintended

00:57:24.350 --> 00:57:26.790
the process of biological development.

00:57:26.790 --> 00:57:29.280
So the Christian can
be open to the evidence

00:57:29.280 --> 00:57:31.240
to follow it where it leads.

00:57:31.240 --> 00:57:34.147
By contrast, as Alvin Plantinga has said,

00:57:34.147 --> 00:57:37.687
"For the naturalist, evolution
is the only game in town.

00:57:37.687 --> 00:57:41.147
"No matter how fantastic the
odds, no matter how improbable,

00:57:41.147 --> 00:57:43.427
"it's got to be true because there is

00:57:43.427 --> 00:57:45.810
"no intelligent creator and designer."

00:57:45.810 --> 00:57:48.060
So in one sense you've
got to feel a little sorry

00:57:48.060 --> 00:57:48.893
for the atheist.

00:57:48.893 --> 00:57:51.920
He can't really follow the
evidence where it leads,

00:57:51.920 --> 00:57:54.830
his presuppositions determine the outcome.

00:57:54.830 --> 00:57:58.650
By contrast, if there is
a fine tuner and creator

00:57:58.650 --> 00:58:01.210
of the universe then
already in the initial

00:58:01.210 --> 00:58:04.880
conditions of the Big Bang you
have an elaborately designed

00:58:04.880 --> 00:58:07.420
universe that permits the
evolution and existence of

00:58:07.420 --> 00:58:10.364
intelligent life and I think
evolution simply layers

00:58:10.364 --> 00:58:12.710
on more improbability.

00:58:12.710 --> 00:58:16.437
Now Mr. Hitchens says, "But
why did God wait so long,

00:58:16.437 --> 00:58:19.787
"all that waste during this time?"

00:58:19.787 --> 00:58:22.461
Well, that sort of concern with efficiency

00:58:22.461 --> 00:58:26.470
is only of importance
to someone with either

00:58:26.470 --> 00:58:30.000
limited time or limited resources or both,

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:33.160
but in the case of God,
He has both unlimited

00:58:33.160 --> 00:58:35.940
resources and unlimited time and therefore

00:58:35.940 --> 00:58:40.570
it's simply not important
to do this in a quick way.

00:58:40.570 --> 00:58:44.217
Well now Mr. Hitchens says,
"But why did God wait so long

00:58:44.217 --> 00:58:45.527
"before he sent Christ?

00:58:45.527 --> 00:58:47.537
"Human beings have existed for thousands

00:58:47.537 --> 00:58:50.960
"of years on this planet
before Christ's coming."

00:58:50.960 --> 00:58:54.640
Well, what's really crucial
here is not the time

00:58:54.640 --> 00:58:57.830
involved rather it's the
population of the world.

00:58:57.830 --> 00:59:00.070
The population reference bureau estimates

00:59:00.070 --> 00:59:01.790
that the number of people
who have ever lived

00:59:01.790 --> 00:59:05.500
on this planet is about
105 billion people.

00:59:05.500 --> 00:59:08.940
Only two percent of them were born prior

00:59:08.940 --> 00:59:11.170
to the advent of Christ.

00:59:11.170 --> 00:59:13.106
Erik Kreps of the Survey Research Center

00:59:13.106 --> 00:59:15.300
of the University of Michigan's Institute

00:59:15.300 --> 00:59:18.417
for Social Research says,
"God's timing couldn't have

00:59:18.417 --> 00:59:19.787
"been more perfect.

00:59:19.787 --> 00:59:22.567
"Christ showed up just
before the exponential

00:59:22.567 --> 00:59:25.920
"explosion in the world's population."

00:59:25.920 --> 00:59:27.967
The Bible says in the fullness of time God

00:59:27.967 --> 00:59:30.856
sent forth His son and when Christ came

00:59:30.856 --> 00:59:33.670
the nation of Israel had been prepared;

00:59:33.670 --> 00:59:36.840
the Roman peace dominated
the Mediterranean world;

00:59:36.840 --> 00:59:38.950
it was an age of literacy and learning;

00:59:38.950 --> 00:59:41.630
the stage was set for the advent of God's

00:59:41.630 --> 00:59:44.930
son into the world and think in God's

00:59:44.930 --> 00:59:47.240
providential plan for human history we see

00:59:47.240 --> 00:59:51.950
the wisdom of God in
orchestrating the development

00:59:51.950 --> 00:59:54.540
of human life and then in bringing Christ

00:59:54.540 --> 00:59:57.470
into the world in the fullness of time.

00:59:57.470 --> 00:59:59.640
So I don't see that there
are any good grounds

00:59:59.640 --> 01:00:04.160
here for thinking that this
provides reason for atheism.

01:00:04.160 --> 01:00:06.753
Now what about my arguments for theism?

01:00:07.740 --> 01:00:09.553
Mr. Hitchens had some
general remarks here.

01:00:09.553 --> 01:00:13.510
He says it's difficult to
get from deism to theism.

01:00:13.510 --> 01:00:15.650
Now I want to point out that's a false

01:00:15.650 --> 01:00:18.670
use of these terms,
this is simply confused.

01:00:18.670 --> 01:00:21.520
Deism is a type of theism.

01:00:21.520 --> 01:00:25.140
Theism is the broad world
view that God exists.

01:00:25.140 --> 01:00:28.230
Deism is a specific kind of theism that

01:00:28.230 --> 01:00:31.680
says God has not revealed
himself directly in the world.

01:00:31.680 --> 01:00:36.350
Now my arguments are a cumulative
case for Christian theism.

01:00:36.350 --> 01:00:39.100
They add up to the belief in the God

01:00:39.100 --> 01:00:41.820
that has been revealed
by Jesus of Nazareth.

01:00:41.820 --> 01:00:43.267
Now Mr. Hitchens says,

01:00:43.267 --> 01:00:45.760
"But you must prove this with certainty."

01:00:45.760 --> 01:00:48.870
Not at all, I am not
claiming these arguments

01:00:48.870 --> 01:00:51.570
demonstrate Christian
theism with certainty.

01:00:51.570 --> 01:00:55.330
I'm saying this is the best
explanation of the data when

01:00:55.330 --> 01:00:58.420
you compare it with other
competing hypotheses.

01:00:58.420 --> 01:01:01.010
I think it's more probable than not.

01:01:01.010 --> 01:01:04.067
He quotes me as to saying,
"The Holy Spirit's witness

01:01:04.067 --> 01:01:07.150
"is the basis for knowing
Christianity to be true,"

01:01:07.150 --> 01:01:08.530
and I affirm that.

01:01:08.530 --> 01:01:11.330
I think the fundamental way
in which we know Christianity

01:01:11.330 --> 01:01:14.370
is true is through the
objective inner witness

01:01:14.370 --> 01:01:15.810
of God's Holy Spirit.

01:01:15.810 --> 01:01:18.750
What I called the immediate knowledge

01:01:18.750 --> 01:01:20.880
of God himself in my fifth point.

01:01:20.880 --> 01:01:24.260
On the basis of that we
have a properly basic

01:01:24.260 --> 01:01:26.037
belief in the existence of God

01:01:26.037 --> 01:01:28.030
and the truth of Christianity.

01:01:28.030 --> 01:01:30.810
But when it comes to showing
someone else that what

01:01:30.810 --> 01:01:32.640
we know through the
witness of the Holy Spirit

01:01:32.640 --> 01:01:34.710
is true here we appeal to argument

01:01:34.710 --> 01:01:36.830
and evidence as I've done tonight.

01:01:36.830 --> 01:01:39.100
And the arguments and
evidence that I've appealed

01:01:39.100 --> 01:01:41.810
to are largely deductive arguments.

01:01:41.810 --> 01:01:43.971
This isn't retrospective evidentialism,

01:01:43.971 --> 01:01:46.200
these are deductive arguments.

01:01:46.200 --> 01:01:47.807
If the premises are true,

01:01:47.807 --> 01:01:50.240
then you cannot deny the conclusions

01:01:50.240 --> 01:01:53.840
on pain of irrationality
because the conclusions follow

01:01:53.840 --> 01:01:56.840
with logical necessity from the premises.

01:01:56.840 --> 01:01:59.690
So the only way to deny the
conclusion is you've got

01:01:59.690 --> 01:02:02.400
to show me which of
the premises are false.

01:02:02.400 --> 01:02:04.520
That's why you've got
that program insert with

01:02:04.520 --> 01:02:08.017
the premises in your
program for these arguments.

01:02:08.017 --> 01:02:10.829
Mr. Hitchens needs to
identify which premises

01:02:10.829 --> 01:02:13.750
of the argument he
rejects as false if he is

01:02:13.750 --> 01:02:15.549
to reject the conclusions.

01:02:15.549 --> 01:02:18.940
Now with respect to my
cosmological argument,

01:02:18.940 --> 01:02:20.950
notice that he didn't
dispute whatever begins

01:02:20.950 --> 01:02:22.656
to exist has a cause, nor did he dispute

01:02:22.656 --> 01:02:25.020
the philosophical and scientific arguments

01:02:25.020 --> 01:02:26.730
for the beginning of the universe.

01:02:26.730 --> 01:02:28.097
All he asked was the question,

01:02:28.097 --> 01:02:30.520
"Was there pre-existent material?"

01:02:30.520 --> 01:02:32.130
The answer is no, there was not.

01:02:32.130 --> 01:02:34.107
As Barrow and Tipler point out,

01:02:34.107 --> 01:02:38.447
"At this singularity, space
and time came into existence.

01:02:38.447 --> 01:02:41.717
"Literally nothing existed
before the singularity.

01:02:41.717 --> 01:02:44.689
"So if the universe originated
at such a singularity,

01:02:44.689 --> 01:02:48.627
"we would truly have a creation ex nihilo,

01:02:48.627 --> 01:02:50.090
"that is, out of nothing."

01:02:50.090 --> 01:02:52.030
And this isn't talking religion, folks,

01:02:52.030 --> 01:02:54.813
this is talking contemporary cosmology.

01:02:54.813 --> 01:02:59.230
So, the first argument, it
seems to me, is unrefuted.

01:02:59.230 --> 01:03:01.723
What about the fine tuning argument?

01:03:02.650 --> 01:03:05.687
Here he said, "Well,
scientists are terribly

01:03:05.687 --> 01:03:08.570
"uncertain about the
fine tuning argument."

01:03:08.570 --> 01:03:11.360
Well, I think that's simply not the case.

01:03:11.360 --> 01:03:15.940
Sir Martin Ryse, the Astronomer
Royal of Great Britain

01:03:15.940 --> 01:03:18.877
has said, "The laws
governing our universe appear

01:03:18.877 --> 01:03:21.477
"to be finely tuned for our existence.

01:03:21.477 --> 01:03:24.787
"Everywhere you look there
are yet more examples.

01:03:24.787 --> 01:03:29.590
"Wherever physicists look they
see examples of fine tuning."

01:03:29.590 --> 01:03:32.777
Ernan McMullen, philosopher
of science, says,

01:03:32.777 --> 01:03:34.787
"It seems safe to say that later theory,

01:03:34.787 --> 01:03:36.777
"no matter how different it may be,

01:03:36.777 --> 01:03:38.797
"will turn up approximately the same

01:03:38.797 --> 01:03:41.117
"numbers and the numerous constraints

01:03:41.117 --> 01:03:43.287
"that have to be imposed on these numbers

01:03:43.287 --> 01:03:45.467
"seem both too specific and too numerous

01:03:45.467 --> 01:03:47.472
"to evaporate entirely."

01:03:47.472 --> 01:03:50.790
So that it's very unlikely
that this fine tuning

01:03:50.790 --> 01:03:53.770
is going to vanish or be explained away.

01:03:53.770 --> 01:03:56.547
Now, Mr. Hitchens responds,

01:03:56.547 --> 01:03:58.767
"But we're headed towards nothingness,

01:03:58.767 --> 01:04:00.577
"we're ultimately going to be doomed

01:04:00.577 --> 01:04:03.010
"and therefore the
universe is not designed."

01:04:03.010 --> 01:04:06.250
Well now, this is not a
very powerful objection.

01:04:06.250 --> 01:04:08.760
The temporal duration of something

01:04:08.760 --> 01:04:11.600
is irrelevant to whether
it's been designed.

01:04:11.600 --> 01:04:13.370
The products of human intelligence

01:04:13.370 --> 01:04:15.860
and engineering like
computers and automobiles

01:04:15.860 --> 01:04:18.135
will eventually decay and cease to exist

01:04:18.135 --> 01:04:20.850
but that doesn't mean
they weren't designed.

01:04:20.850 --> 01:04:22.580
I think the real objection
that he's getting

01:04:22.580 --> 01:04:25.600
at here is why would God create mankind

01:04:25.600 --> 01:04:27.720
only to have it go extinct?

01:04:27.720 --> 01:04:30.810
But of course, you see, on the
Christian view that's false,

01:04:30.810 --> 01:04:32.980
that is an atheistic assumption.

01:04:32.980 --> 01:04:35.830
On the Christian view life
does not end at the grave

01:04:35.830 --> 01:04:37.510
and God has given assurance of this

01:04:37.510 --> 01:04:39.520
by raising Jesus from the dead.

01:04:39.520 --> 01:04:42.100
So the objection simply has no purchase

01:04:42.100 --> 01:04:44.210
against Christian theism.

01:04:44.210 --> 01:04:46.150
So it seems to me that the fine tuning

01:04:46.150 --> 01:04:48.610
argument is also unrefuted.

01:04:48.610 --> 01:04:50.320
What about the moral argument?

01:04:50.320 --> 01:04:53.260
We saw that without God there
are no objective moral values,

01:04:53.260 --> 01:04:56.880
Mr. Hitchens agrees with this
and yet he himself affirms

01:04:56.880 --> 01:04:59.160
over and over again moral statements like

01:04:59.160 --> 01:05:04.160
the moral reprobation
of religious intolerance

01:05:04.498 --> 01:05:06.820
and violence in the name of religion.

01:05:06.820 --> 01:05:08.746
So he does affirm objective values,

01:05:08.746 --> 01:05:10.620
but without any basis for it.

01:05:10.620 --> 01:05:13.860
What I can offer him as a
theist is a transcendent

01:05:13.860 --> 01:05:16.384
basis for the objective
moral values and duties

01:05:16.384 --> 01:05:18.690
that we both want to affirm.

01:05:18.690 --> 01:05:20.540
Fourthly, the resurrection of Jesus.

01:05:20.540 --> 01:05:22.810
Again, there was no response to this.

01:05:22.810 --> 01:05:24.710
Let me simply quote N.T. Wright

01:05:24.710 --> 01:05:26.910
in his recent study of the resurrection.

01:05:26.910 --> 01:05:29.547
He says that, "The empty
tomb and the appearances

01:05:29.547 --> 01:05:32.917
"of Jesus have a historical
probability so high

01:05:32.917 --> 01:05:34.947
"as to be virtually certain,

01:05:34.947 --> 01:05:37.917
"like the death of Augustus in AD 14

01:05:37.917 --> 01:05:41.260
"or the fall of Jerusalem in AD 70."

01:05:41.260 --> 01:05:43.940
So we are on very solid
ground in affirming

01:05:43.940 --> 01:05:46.670
these three facts that I
mentioned in my opening speech

01:05:46.670 --> 01:05:48.820
and I can't think of
any better explanation

01:05:48.820 --> 01:05:50.830
than the ones that the eye witnesses gave,

01:05:50.830 --> 01:05:53.400
namely that God raised
Jesus from the dead.

01:05:53.400 --> 01:05:55.980
Finally, the immediate experience of God.

01:05:55.980 --> 01:05:58.446
Unless Mr. Hitchens can show
that I'm psychologically

01:05:58.446 --> 01:06:00.930
deranged or delusional,

01:06:00.930 --> 01:06:03.010
it seems to me I'm perfectly rational

01:06:03.010 --> 01:06:05.070
on the basis of my immediate experience

01:06:05.070 --> 01:06:07.900
of God to believe that God exists

01:06:07.900 --> 01:06:11.010
and that therefore this, for
me, is a properly basic belief.

01:06:11.010 --> 01:06:13.000
So I think all of these arguments stand

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:14.920
intact despite his reputation.

01:06:14.920 --> 01:06:17.680
We've seen no argument for atheism,

01:06:17.680 --> 01:06:20.090
so clearly the weight
of the evidence falls

01:06:20.090 --> 01:06:23.133
on the side of the scale for
Christian theism tonight.

01:06:25.439 --> 01:06:28.439
[audience applause]

01:06:44.279 --> 01:06:46.240
&gt;&gt; There is a terminological problem here

01:06:46.240 --> 01:06:50.690
which may conceal more than
just terminological difficulty.

01:06:50.690 --> 01:06:53.360
The proposition that atheism is true

01:06:53.360 --> 01:06:57.990
or is a misstatement
of what I have to prove

01:06:57.990 --> 01:06:59.680
and what we believe.

01:06:59.680 --> 01:07:01.640
There's an argument among some of us as to

01:07:01.640 --> 01:07:03.010
whether that we need the word at all.

01:07:03.010 --> 01:07:06.430
In other words, I don't
have a special name

01:07:06.430 --> 01:07:10.900
for my unbelief in tooth
fairies, say, or witches,

01:07:10.900 --> 01:07:12.420
or in Santa Claus.

01:07:12.420 --> 01:07:14.320
I just don't think that they're there.

01:07:14.320 --> 01:07:16.463
I don't have to prove "atoothfairyism."

01:07:16.463 --> 01:07:19.083
I don't have to prove "asantaclausism."

01:07:19.083 --> 01:07:21.070
I don't have to prove "awitchism."

01:07:21.070 --> 01:07:23.440
It's just, I have to
say, I think that those

01:07:23.440 --> 01:07:26.440
who do believe these
things have never been

01:07:26.440 --> 01:07:31.440
able to make a plausible or
intelligible case for doing so.

01:07:31.690 --> 01:07:33.510
That's not agnosticism
because it seems to me

01:07:33.510 --> 01:07:35.710
that if you don't think
that there is any evidence

01:07:35.710 --> 01:07:37.850
you're wrong to take refuge
in saying you're neutral.

01:07:37.850 --> 01:07:39.950
You ought to have the courage
to answer the question

01:07:39.950 --> 01:07:42.990
which one is regularly asked,
"Are you an atheist or not?"

01:07:42.990 --> 01:07:44.980
Yes, I will say, I am.

01:07:44.980 --> 01:07:46.798
You can't tell anything else about me.

01:07:46.798 --> 01:07:48.700
You can't tell anything
else about what I think,

01:07:48.700 --> 01:07:52.624
about what I believe,
about what my politics are

01:07:52.624 --> 01:07:53.910
or my other convictions.

01:07:53.910 --> 01:07:55.740
It's just that I don't believe in the

01:07:55.740 --> 01:07:58.840
existence of a supernatural dimension.

01:07:58.840 --> 01:08:01.900
I've never been shown any
evidence that any process

01:08:01.900 --> 01:08:06.320
observable to us cannot
be explained by more

01:08:06.320 --> 01:08:10.520
satisfactory and more convincing means.

01:08:10.520 --> 01:08:14.400
The great physicist
Laplace, when showing his

01:08:14.400 --> 01:08:16.410
working model of the solar system to the

01:08:16.410 --> 01:08:17.607
Emperor Napoleon, was asked,

01:08:17.607 --> 01:08:22.607
"Well, you're model seems to
have no room for God in it,

01:08:22.697 --> 01:08:25.317
"for a deity," and he
said, "Well, Your Majesty,

01:08:25.317 --> 01:08:28.377
"it still all operates
without that assumption."

01:08:29.820 --> 01:08:34.820
Now, here's what you
would have to believe if

01:08:35.860 --> 01:08:38.753
you thought that this was all designed.

01:08:40.860 --> 01:08:44.450
Dr. Craig gave a slight parody
of what I think about this.

01:08:44.450 --> 01:08:47.380
It could be true, but
you'd have to imagine,

01:08:47.380 --> 01:08:49.040
let's say the human species has been,

01:08:49.040 --> 01:08:51.370
Homo sapiens has been with us, some people

01:08:51.370 --> 01:08:53.470
say as long as quarter of a million years,

01:08:55.430 --> 01:08:58.600
some say 200, some say 100,000.

01:08:58.600 --> 01:09:00.653
Francis Collins and Richard
Dawkins oscillate about this.

01:09:00.653 --> 01:09:02.580
It's not a very big argument.

01:09:02.580 --> 01:09:04.990
I'll just take 100,000 if you like.

01:09:04.990 --> 01:09:08.223
You have to imagine that
human beings are born,

01:09:09.120 --> 01:09:11.040
well actually most of them, a good number

01:09:11.040 --> 01:09:13.410
of them aren't born,
they die in childbirth

01:09:13.410 --> 01:09:15.670
or don't long outlive it.

01:09:15.670 --> 01:09:20.450
They're born into a terrifying
world of the unknown,

01:09:20.450 --> 01:09:22.060
everything is a mystery
to them, everything

01:09:22.060 --> 01:09:24.663
from disease to volcanic eruptions.

01:09:26.700 --> 01:09:30.370
Everything is, life
expectancy for the first,

01:09:30.370 --> 01:09:32.800
I don't know, many, many tens of thousands

01:09:32.800 --> 01:09:35.110
of years would be lucky
to be in the twenties,

01:09:35.110 --> 01:09:38.420
probably dying agonizingly of their teeth,

01:09:38.420 --> 01:09:41.666
poorly evolved as the teeth
are and from other inheritances

01:09:41.666 --> 01:09:43.820
from being primates such as the appendix

01:09:43.820 --> 01:09:46.130
that we don't need, such as the fact that

01:09:46.130 --> 01:09:48.670
our genitalia appear to be
designed by a committee,

01:09:48.670 --> 01:09:53.670
other short comings of the
species, exaggerated by scarcity,

01:09:54.770 --> 01:09:58.170
by war, by famine, by
competition and so on and for

01:09:58.170 --> 01:10:01.410
98,000 years or so
heaven watches this with

01:10:01.410 --> 01:10:04.683
complete indifference.
[phone pings]

01:10:06.030 --> 01:10:08.680
We know where your children
go to school, by the way.

01:10:09.990 --> 01:10:11.710
Heaven watches this
with total indifference

01:10:11.710 --> 01:10:15.047
and then with 2,000 years
to go on the clock thinks,

01:10:15.047 --> 01:10:16.797
"Actually, it's time we intervened.

01:10:17.967 --> 01:10:20.487
"We can't go on like this,
why don't we have someone

01:10:20.487 --> 01:10:24.527
"tortured to death in
Bronze Age Palestine?

01:10:24.527 --> 01:10:26.127
"That should teach them;

01:10:26.127 --> 01:10:29.050
"that should give them
a chance at redemption."

01:10:29.050 --> 01:10:32.336
You're free to believe that,
but I think the designer who

01:10:32.336 --> 01:10:35.560
thought of doing it that way is a very,

01:10:35.560 --> 01:10:39.300
or was a very cruel,
capricious, random, bungling,

01:10:39.300 --> 01:10:40.440
and incompetent one.

01:10:40.440 --> 01:10:43.052
The news of this, Dr. Craig talks as if,

01:10:43.052 --> 01:10:46.527
"Okay, but since then
they'll be more people born

01:10:46.527 --> 01:10:48.437
"so it might have been
a good time in terms

01:10:48.437 --> 01:10:50.560
"of population growth,"
well, there are a huge number

01:10:50.560 --> 01:10:54.080
of people who still haven't
even heard of this idea.

01:10:54.080 --> 01:10:56.930
The news hasn't penetrated
to them, or where it has,

01:10:56.930 --> 01:10:58.660
it's been brought to them
by people who Dr. Craig

01:10:58.660 --> 01:11:01.890
doesn't think of as
Christians, such as Mormons,

01:11:01.890 --> 01:11:05.520
for example, and it's
taught to them in many

01:11:05.520 --> 01:11:08.490
discrepant and competitive
and indeed incompatible

01:11:08.490 --> 01:11:11.420
and violently irreconcilable ways.

01:11:11.420 --> 01:11:13.750
And there's been a lot
of argument in the church

01:11:13.750 --> 01:11:16.347
and the churches all
this time about, well,

01:11:16.347 --> 01:11:17.627
"Okay, what is the answer to that?

01:11:17.627 --> 01:11:19.657
"What about all the
people who never could've

01:11:19.657 --> 01:11:22.387
"heard the good news or
who never will hear it

01:11:22.387 --> 01:11:23.847
"or still haven't been reached by it

01:11:23.847 --> 01:11:25.337
"and who've died not knowing about it?

01:11:25.337 --> 01:11:26.337
"What happens to them?

01:11:26.337 --> 01:11:27.290
"How can they be saved?"

01:11:27.290 --> 01:11:28.940
Well the argument is that it's all

01:11:28.940 --> 01:11:30.719
somehow made retrospective.

01:11:30.719 --> 01:11:33.330
And as, with so many of these arguments,

01:11:33.330 --> 01:11:35.653
I just comment on these,
well how convenient.

01:11:36.910 --> 01:11:38.190
Because if you're willing
to make assumptions

01:11:38.190 --> 01:11:41.090
of this kind then really
evidence is only ancillary

01:11:41.090 --> 01:11:44.510
to what you are advancing.

01:11:44.510 --> 01:11:48.200
Now I didn't have to chance,
oh, and just on Mr. Wright,

01:11:48.200 --> 01:11:50.250
sorry I scrawled a little note to myself,

01:11:52.240 --> 01:11:55.357
in your first round, Doctor,
you said that N.T. Wright,

01:11:55.357 --> 01:12:00.270
who is an impressive person,
says that no explanation

01:12:00.270 --> 01:12:02.910
of the success of Christianity is possible

01:12:02.910 --> 01:12:06.020
that doesn't rest on the
terms of its being true,

01:12:06.020 --> 01:12:08.617
in other words Wright says,
"It was so successful,

01:12:08.617 --> 01:12:10.897
"it must have been that
the people were so strongly

01:12:10.897 --> 01:12:13.290
"motivated to believe it,
that it must have been true."

01:12:13.290 --> 01:12:15.910
I regard that as a very,
very unsafe assumption.

01:12:15.910 --> 01:12:18.670
Or, if it is a safe
one, then it must surely

01:12:18.670 --> 01:12:21.260
apply to Islam and to Mormonism.

01:12:21.260 --> 01:12:22.430
I mean, these are two very, very,

01:12:22.430 --> 01:12:24.030
very fast growing religions;

01:12:24.030 --> 01:12:27.189
have people prepared to
sacrifice enormously for it;

01:12:27.189 --> 01:12:30.020
have ancestors who were
absolutely determined

01:12:30.020 --> 01:12:31.980
of the truth of it at the time and who

01:12:31.980 --> 01:12:34.433
made extraordinary conquests in its name.

01:12:35.340 --> 01:12:36.900
If you're going to grant
this for one religion

01:12:36.900 --> 01:12:39.330
it seems to me you have to
be willing, not just willing,

01:12:39.330 --> 01:12:42.595
you may indeed be compelled
to make this concession

01:12:42.595 --> 01:12:44.400
for all of them and that, I think,

01:12:44.400 --> 01:12:45.910
would be not just an unsafe assumption

01:12:45.910 --> 01:12:49.090
but for most of you here a
distinctly unwelcome one.

01:12:49.090 --> 01:12:52.630
Now, I didn't get the chance,
because I out-talked myself,

01:12:52.630 --> 01:12:56.005
I'm sorry for it, to get
to the moral dimension

01:12:56.005 --> 01:12:59.130
and I'm interested in the
fact that "objective" morality

01:12:59.130 --> 01:13:01.190
is the one that Dr. Craig chooses.

01:13:01.190 --> 01:13:03.010
Usually the arguments about
morality are whether the

01:13:03.010 --> 01:13:05.330
morality as, so to say, "absolute,"

01:13:05.330 --> 01:13:07.180
or whether it's "relative."

01:13:07.180 --> 01:13:09.580
As to objectivity I think
it's a very good compromise

01:13:09.580 --> 01:13:13.690
word by the way and I'm
very happy to accept it.

01:13:13.690 --> 01:13:17.070
But the problem with morality is this,

01:13:17.070 --> 01:13:18.500
in respect of religion:

01:13:18.500 --> 01:13:22.600
You can't prove that
anyone behaves any better

01:13:22.600 --> 01:13:24.760
if they refer to this problem upward to

01:13:24.760 --> 01:13:28.653
a supreme dictator of a celestial kind.

01:13:29.900 --> 01:13:33.312
There are two questions
that I've asked in public

01:13:33.312 --> 01:13:35.590
and I'll try them again because I try them

01:13:35.590 --> 01:13:37.010
on every audience.

01:13:37.010 --> 01:13:38.100
They're very simple ones.

01:13:38.100 --> 01:13:41.310
First, you have to name
for me, challenges,

01:13:41.310 --> 01:13:42.970
let's say, rather than
questions, you have to name

01:13:42.970 --> 01:13:46.110
for me an ethical action
or an ethical statement

01:13:46.110 --> 01:13:49.690
or moral action or moral
statement made or undertaken

01:13:49.690 --> 01:13:53.850
by a believer that I
couldn't undertake or say,

01:13:53.850 --> 01:13:55.253
I couldn't state or do.

01:13:56.480 --> 01:13:59.050
I haven't yet had an example
pointed out of that to me.

01:13:59.050 --> 01:14:01.490
In other words, that a
person of faith would

01:14:01.490 --> 01:14:03.460
have an advantage by being able to call

01:14:03.460 --> 01:14:05.810
upon divine sanction.

01:14:05.810 --> 01:14:08.590
Whereas if I ask you to think
of a wicked act undertaken

01:14:08.590 --> 01:14:12.340
by someone in the name of
God or because of their faith

01:14:12.340 --> 01:14:14.270
or a wicked statement
made, you wouldn't have

01:14:14.270 --> 01:14:15.950
that much difficulty,
I think, in coming up

01:14:15.950 --> 01:14:18.110
with an example right away.

01:14:18.110 --> 01:14:20.510
The genital mutilation
community, for example,

01:14:20.510 --> 01:14:22.460
is almost exclusively religious;

01:14:22.460 --> 01:14:24.390
the suicide bombing community

01:14:24.390 --> 01:14:26.850
is almost exclusively religious;

01:14:26.850 --> 01:14:30.670
there are injunctions for
genocide in the Old Testament;

01:14:30.670 --> 01:14:32.700
there are injunctions,
warrants for slavery

01:14:32.700 --> 01:14:34.890
and racism in the Old Testament too.

01:14:34.890 --> 01:14:37.920
There's simply no way of deriving morality

01:14:37.920 --> 01:14:39.953
and ethics from the supernatural.

01:14:41.150 --> 01:14:44.470
When we come to the question
of the absolute, well,

01:14:44.470 --> 01:14:48.030
the most often cited
one is the Golden Rule,

01:14:48.030 --> 01:14:50.600
the one that almost everyone
feels they have in common.

01:14:50.600 --> 01:14:52.630
The injunction not to do to others as you

01:14:52.630 --> 01:14:54.730
wouldn't want them to do to you.

01:14:54.730 --> 01:14:56.810
This doesn't in fact come
from the Sermon on the Mount

01:14:56.810 --> 01:14:59.690
or from Christianity, or it
doesn't originate with it.

01:14:59.690 --> 01:15:01.620
It's certainly adumbrated by Rabbi Hillel,

01:15:01.620 --> 01:15:03.350
a Babylonian rabbi,
and it's to be found in

01:15:03.350 --> 01:15:05.440
The Analects of Confucius, too.

01:15:05.440 --> 01:15:08.850
But it has, since we're talking
about objective, relative,

01:15:08.850 --> 01:15:12.640
and absolute, a crucial
weakness in it, unfortunately.

01:15:12.640 --> 01:15:13.780
We'd like to be able to follow it

01:15:13.780 --> 01:15:17.067
but it's really only as good
as the person uttering it.

01:15:17.067 --> 01:15:20.290
In others words, if I
say I won't treat you

01:15:20.290 --> 01:15:22.370
as I don't want you to treat me,

01:15:22.370 --> 01:15:24.970
what am I to do when
confronted with Charles Manson?

01:15:25.920 --> 01:15:27.458
I want him treated in a way that

01:15:27.458 --> 01:15:30.200
I wouldn't want to be treated myself.

01:15:30.200 --> 01:15:34.370
Anything else would surely
be completely relativistic.

01:15:34.370 --> 01:15:37.180
So the argument isn't at all advanced

01:15:37.180 --> 01:15:39.900
by saying that I couldn't
know any of this;

01:15:39.900 --> 01:15:42.380
I couldn't have any moral promptings;

01:15:42.380 --> 01:15:45.190
I couldn't decide for myself
if I see a pregnant woman

01:15:45.190 --> 01:15:48.150
being kicked in the stomach
that, because she's pregnant,

01:15:48.150 --> 01:15:51.150
that's obviously worse than if it was just

01:15:51.150 --> 01:15:53.740
a woman who wasn't pregnant
being kicked in the stomach.

01:15:53.740 --> 01:15:57.010
This is part of my
patrimony as a human being.

01:15:57.010 --> 01:16:00.010
It's part of the essential
emotional solidarity

01:16:00.010 --> 01:16:03.000
that I need to have
with my fellow creatures

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:06.010
to make us realize that we
are brothers and sisters,

01:16:06.010 --> 01:16:07.160
one with another.

01:16:07.160 --> 01:16:09.520
We are dependent upon each
other; we have duties;

01:16:09.520 --> 01:16:12.240
we have expectations
of one another and that

01:16:12.240 --> 01:16:14.440
if we didn't have these,
and try and fulfill them,

01:16:14.440 --> 01:16:16.350
we couldn't have gotten as far as we have.

01:16:16.350 --> 01:16:18.630
We couldn't have evolved as a species;

01:16:18.630 --> 01:16:20.650
we couldn't have ever had a society.

01:16:20.650 --> 01:16:23.320
There's never been a
society found where rape

01:16:23.320 --> 01:16:26.534
and murder and perjury are not condemned.

01:16:26.534 --> 01:16:30.100
These moral discoveries
long, or absolutes,

01:16:30.100 --> 01:16:32.350
if you want to call
them that, long predate

01:16:32.350 --> 01:16:36.860
the arrival of anything
recognizable as monotheism.

01:16:36.860 --> 01:16:39.810
It's a bit like the argument of free will.

01:16:39.810 --> 01:16:43.517
People say, "Well, how
do you have free will?

01:16:43.517 --> 01:16:44.780
"Do you think you do have it?"

01:16:44.780 --> 01:16:47.980
Well, it's a very, very
difficult subject indeed.

01:16:47.980 --> 01:16:50.223
Some religions say you
don't in effect have it.

01:16:50.223 --> 01:16:52.530
That all is determined
by heaven, you're really

01:16:52.530 --> 01:16:54.400
only a play thing in a larger game.

01:16:54.400 --> 01:16:57.910
I take that to be that some
of the point of Calvinism.

01:16:57.910 --> 01:16:59.737
There are some schools
of Islam also that say,

01:16:59.737 --> 01:17:02.222
"It is only as Allah wills."

01:17:02.222 --> 01:17:04.970
There's no will of yours really involved

01:17:04.970 --> 01:17:06.776
as long as you're willing
to make the prostration

01:17:06.776 --> 01:17:08.120
and the obedience.

01:17:08.120 --> 01:17:09.830
So the connection between
religion and free will

01:17:09.830 --> 01:17:13.193
isn't as simple, as easy
as some people think it is.

01:17:14.220 --> 01:17:16.647
But I would say, yes, I
think we have free will.

01:17:16.647 --> 01:17:20.320
And when asked why I think so,
I would have to take refuge

01:17:20.320 --> 01:17:21.897
in philosophical irony and say,

01:17:21.897 --> 01:17:23.827
"Because I don't think we have any choice

01:17:23.827 --> 01:17:26.780
"but to have free will."
[audience laughing]

01:17:26.780 --> 01:17:30.830
Well at least I know at
this point that I'm being

01:17:30.830 --> 01:17:33.540
ironic and that some of
the irony is at my own

01:17:33.540 --> 01:17:37.150
expense and it's a risk I
have to be willing to run.

01:17:37.150 --> 01:17:38.507
But the Christian answer is,

01:17:38.507 --> 01:17:42.357
"Of course you have free will,
the boss insists upon it."

01:17:43.428 --> 01:17:44.830
[audience laughing]

01:17:44.830 --> 01:17:47.870
This somewhat degrades
the freedom and redefines

01:17:47.870 --> 01:17:51.010
the idea of will and it seems to me also

01:17:51.010 --> 01:17:52.810
that there's something
degrading in the idea

01:17:52.810 --> 01:17:56.200
of that saying that morality
is derived in the same way.

01:17:56.200 --> 01:17:59.460
That it comes from on
high; that we, ourselves,

01:17:59.460 --> 01:18:02.450
are not good enough, that
we don't have the dignity,

01:18:02.450 --> 01:18:03.730
we don't have the self respect,

01:18:03.730 --> 01:18:06.310
we don't have the character
to know a right action

01:18:06.310 --> 01:18:07.780
or a right statement when we see it

01:18:07.780 --> 01:18:09.900
or when we want to perform it.

01:18:09.900 --> 01:18:12.610
It's this servile element in religion.

01:18:12.610 --> 01:18:14.320
It's not strictly speaking the subject

01:18:14.320 --> 01:18:16.440
of our debate this evening,
I know, but I'm damned

01:18:16.440 --> 01:18:20.360
if I completely forgo
it, it's the idea that,

01:18:20.360 --> 01:18:21.730
buried in the religious impulse,

01:18:21.730 --> 01:18:24.790
is actually the wish to
be unfree, is the wish

01:18:24.790 --> 01:18:29.630
for an immovable, unchangeable,
celestial authority,

01:18:29.630 --> 01:18:34.630
a kind of heavenly North Korea
that will take our decisions

01:18:36.277 --> 01:18:38.810
away from us and commit us only to worship

01:18:38.810 --> 01:18:42.840
and praise and thank a
Great Leader and his son,

01:18:42.840 --> 01:18:45.570
the Dear Leader, forever
and ever and ever.

01:18:45.570 --> 01:18:47.480
I'm so glad that there's no
evidence that this is true.

01:18:47.480 --> 01:18:48.313
Thank you.

01:18:50.055 --> 01:18:53.055
[audience applause]

01:18:59.200 --> 01:19:02.660
&gt;&gt; We now enter the period
of cross examination which,

01:19:02.660 --> 01:19:06.580
trial like, allows the questioner to pose

01:19:06.580 --> 01:19:09.030
and the answerer only to
answer and not to repeat the

01:19:09.030 --> 01:19:10.730
question or to dodge.

01:19:10.730 --> 01:19:13.540
Six minutes of questions
begin to Dr. Craig

01:19:13.540 --> 01:19:16.190
followed by six minutes of
questions to Mr. Hitchens.

01:19:16.190 --> 01:19:18.520
Dr. Craig, your questions
for Mr. Hitchens.

01:19:18.520 --> 01:19:19.353
&gt;&gt; All right.

01:19:19.353 --> 01:19:22.200
Let's talk first about whether
there are any good arguments

01:19:22.200 --> 01:19:24.740
to think that atheism is true.

01:19:24.740 --> 01:19:28.570
Now, it seems to me that
you're rather ambivalent here,

01:19:28.570 --> 01:19:32.930
that you say, you redefine atheism to mean

01:19:32.930 --> 01:19:36.917
a sort of ah-theism or non-theism.

01:19:36.917 --> 01:19:39.220
&gt;&gt; Christopher: That's what it means.

01:19:39.220 --> 01:19:42.120
&gt;&gt; But, how do you distinguish, then,

01:19:42.120 --> 01:19:45.070
the different varieties of non-theism.

01:19:45.070 --> 01:19:48.439
For example, what is
normally called atheism,

01:19:48.439 --> 01:19:52.505
agnosticism, or the view
of verificationists,

01:19:52.505 --> 01:19:56.073
the statement "God exists"
is simply meaningless?

01:19:57.870 --> 01:19:59.480
&gt;&gt; Well, I mean, there
are different schools

01:19:59.480 --> 01:20:02.470
of atheism as you say,
but there's no claim

01:20:02.470 --> 01:20:04.972
I know how to make that
says atheism is true

01:20:04.972 --> 01:20:06.553
because atheism is the statement that

01:20:06.553 --> 01:20:08.960
a certain proposition isn't true.

01:20:08.960 --> 01:20:11.760
So I wish you'd get
this bit right because,

01:20:11.760 --> 01:20:13.700
there you go again.

01:20:13.700 --> 01:20:15.930
I've just devoted a little time to this.

01:20:15.930 --> 01:20:20.627
I said it is not, in itself,
a belief or a system,

01:20:20.627 --> 01:20:25.627
it simply says you can by
get by better, probably,

01:20:25.670 --> 01:20:27.320
we think, without the assumption

01:20:27.320 --> 01:20:29.810
and that no one who wants you to worship

01:20:29.810 --> 01:20:31.570
a god has ever been able to come up with

01:20:31.570 --> 01:20:33.470
a good enough reason to make you to do it.

01:20:33.470 --> 01:20:35.610
&gt;&gt; Now, so, the point is, though,

01:20:35.610 --> 01:20:40.170
that on your definition of ah-theism

01:20:40.170 --> 01:20:44.230
or nontheism, it really
embodies a diversity

01:20:44.230 --> 01:20:46.690
of views such as agnosticism,

01:20:46.690 --> 01:20:51.477
what is normally called atheism,
or this verificationism.

01:20:52.920 --> 01:20:55.700
Now, which of those do you hold to within

01:20:55.700 --> 01:20:57.550
this umbrella of ah-theism?

01:20:57.550 --> 01:21:01.477
Are you an atheist who
asserts the proposition

01:21:01.477 --> 01:21:04.840
"God does not exist" or
do you simply withhold

01:21:04.840 --> 01:21:07.660
belief in God in the way
that the agnostic does?

01:21:07.660 --> 01:21:08.493
&gt;&gt; Right.

01:21:09.870 --> 01:21:14.460
On some days I'm a great--
[audience laughing]

01:21:14.460 --> 01:21:16.513
No, I'm not going to do
you that much of a favor.

01:21:18.147 --> 01:21:20.590
On some days I'm a great
admirer of Thomas Huxley

01:21:20.590 --> 01:21:24.250
who had the great debate
with Bishop Wilberforce

01:21:24.250 --> 01:21:27.890
in Oxford at the Natural
History Museum about Darwinism

01:21:27.890 --> 01:21:29.850
in the mid-19th century,

01:21:29.850 --> 01:21:32.000
who was known as Darwin's bulldog.

01:21:32.000 --> 01:21:34.400
We would now say Darwin's pitbull.

01:21:34.400 --> 01:21:36.600
And who completely
trounced the good bishop.

01:21:37.610 --> 01:21:39.777
But, I can't thank him
for inventing the term

01:21:39.777 --> 01:21:42.500
"agnostic" and I can't
thank him for some of

01:21:42.500 --> 01:21:43.723
his social Darwinist positions either,

01:21:43.723 --> 01:21:45.160
some of which are rather unattractive--

01:21:45.160 --> 01:21:46.897
&gt;&gt; I need an answer to
this, my time is fleeting.

01:21:46.897 --> 01:21:50.450
&gt;&gt; Yes, because I think
agnosticism is evasive.

01:21:50.450 --> 01:21:52.790
To me, yes, if you talk about the power

01:21:52.790 --> 01:21:54.140
of the Holy Spirit and so forth,

01:21:54.140 --> 01:21:57.210
to me that is meaningless,
it's, to me, I'm sorry,

01:21:57.210 --> 01:21:59.580
I've tried, it's white noise.

01:21:59.580 --> 01:22:01.387
It's like saying, "There is only one God

01:22:01.387 --> 01:22:02.920
"and Allah is his messenger."

01:22:02.920 --> 01:22:04.399
It's gibberish to me.

01:22:04.399 --> 01:22:07.130
There are many of us, I'm
sorry there are just many

01:22:07.130 --> 01:22:10.220
of us to whom, of whom this is the case.

01:22:10.220 --> 01:22:13.120
It may be true, it is true that religion--

01:22:13.120 --> 01:22:14.120
&gt;&gt; William: I gotta press you here,

01:22:14.120 --> 01:22:15.690
'cause time is fleeting.

01:22:15.690 --> 01:22:18.351
What is your view exactly?
&gt;&gt; Press away.

01:22:18.351 --> 01:22:20.734
&gt;&gt; Do you affirm God does not exist,

01:22:20.734 --> 01:22:22.396
or do you simply withhold belief?

01:22:22.396 --> 01:22:24.340
&gt;&gt; I think once I have said
that I've never seen any

01:22:24.340 --> 01:22:26.650
persuasive evidence for
the existence of something,

01:22:26.650 --> 01:22:30.400
and I've made real attempts to
study the evidence presented

01:22:30.400 --> 01:22:31.233
and the arguments presented,

01:22:31.233 --> 01:22:33.730
that I will go as far as to say,

01:22:33.730 --> 01:22:37.290
have the nerve to say, that
it does not therefore exist

01:22:37.290 --> 01:22:38.450
except in the minds of its--

01:22:38.450 --> 01:22:39.592
&gt;&gt; William: All right, so--

01:22:39.592 --> 01:22:43.750
&gt;&gt; Except in the Henry
Jamesian subject of sense

01:22:43.750 --> 01:22:47.250
that you say of it being
so real to some people

01:22:47.250 --> 01:22:50.990
in their own minds that it
counts as a force in the world.

01:22:50.990 --> 01:22:52.970
&gt;&gt; Craig: Okay, so you do affirm then

01:22:52.970 --> 01:22:54.660
that God does not exist.

01:22:54.660 --> 01:22:56.200
Now, what I want to know, and do you have

01:22:56.200 --> 01:22:58.590
any justification for that?

01:22:58.590 --> 01:23:00.418
&gt;&gt; I think I've come unwired.

01:23:00.418 --> 01:23:01.251
&gt;&gt; William: You're fine.

01:23:01.251 --> 01:23:02.740
&gt;&gt; Are you sure?
[audience laughing]

01:23:02.740 --> 01:23:07.100
&gt;&gt; Do you have any arguments
leading to the conclusion

01:23:07.100 --> 01:23:09.540
that God does not exist?

01:23:09.540 --> 01:23:11.660
&gt;&gt; Well I would rather,
I think, I'm wondering

01:23:11.660 --> 01:23:13.290
if I'm boring anybody now.

01:23:13.290 --> 01:23:17.380
I would rather say, I'd
rather state it in reverse

01:23:17.380 --> 01:23:19.820
and say I find all the arguments in favor

01:23:19.820 --> 01:23:22.532
to be fallacious or unconvincing.

01:23:22.532 --> 01:23:25.600
And I'd have to add, that
though this isn't my reason

01:23:25.600 --> 01:23:28.300
for not believing in it, that
I would be very depressed

01:23:28.300 --> 01:23:29.690
if it was true.

01:23:29.690 --> 01:23:31.948
That's quite a different thing.

01:23:31.948 --> 01:23:35.350
I don't say of atheism that
it's at all morally superior,

01:23:35.350 --> 01:23:36.310
that would be very risky.

01:23:36.310 --> 01:23:38.450
I wouldn't admit that it was
at all morally inferior either,

01:23:38.450 --> 01:23:39.990
but we can at least be acquitted

01:23:39.990 --> 01:23:42.030
on the charge of wishful thinking.

01:23:42.030 --> 01:23:42.863
We don't particularly--

01:23:42.863 --> 01:23:44.850
&gt;&gt; I wonder if that's the case.

01:23:44.850 --> 01:23:48.009
Would you agree that
the absence of evidence

01:23:48.009 --> 01:23:50.323
is not evidence of absence?

01:23:51.490 --> 01:23:54.770
&gt;&gt; Well you know, I'm not
sure that I would agree.

01:23:54.770 --> 01:23:55.730
&gt;&gt; Okay.

01:23:55.730 --> 01:23:57.827
Let's turn to the moral
argument and talk about that

01:23:57.827 --> 01:23:58.660
a little bit.

01:23:58.660 --> 01:24:01.456
I think you've misunderstood
the moral argument--

01:24:01.456 --> 01:24:04.610
&gt;&gt; Given the stakes, Doctor,
sorry, given the stakes,

01:24:04.610 --> 01:24:06.030
I mean you're not
saying, we're not talking

01:24:06.030 --> 01:24:09.460
about unicorns or tooth
fairies or leprechauns here,

01:24:09.460 --> 01:24:11.800
we're talking about an
authority that would

01:24:11.800 --> 01:24:15.230
give other humans beings the
right to tell me what to do

01:24:15.230 --> 01:24:16.470
in the name of God.

01:24:16.470 --> 01:24:19.940
So, for a claim like that if
there's no evidence for it,

01:24:19.940 --> 01:24:21.833
it seems to me a very,

01:24:22.830 --> 01:24:24.900
not a small question.

01:24:24.900 --> 01:24:26.690
&gt;&gt; No, it's certainly
not a small question.

01:24:26.690 --> 01:24:28.960
&gt;&gt; Because you're making a
very, very, very large claim.

01:24:28.960 --> 01:24:31.240
Your evidence had been be
absolutely magnificent,

01:24:31.240 --> 01:24:32.200
it seems to me.

01:24:32.200 --> 01:24:33.740
and it's the lack of magnificence

01:24:33.740 --> 01:24:36.250
I think that began to strike me first.

01:24:36.250 --> 01:24:37.730
&gt;&gt; Hugh: One final question, doctor.

01:24:37.730 --> 01:24:39.440
&gt;&gt; Okay, well let's go
to the moral argument.

01:24:39.440 --> 01:24:41.240
It seems to me there
that you've misunderstood

01:24:41.240 --> 01:24:44.240
the argument, in that we're looking for an

01:24:44.240 --> 01:24:47.550
objective foundation for the moral values

01:24:47.550 --> 01:24:50.320
and duties that we want, we
both I think want to affirm.

01:24:50.320 --> 01:24:53.060
It's not a matter of
whether or not we can know

01:24:53.060 --> 01:24:55.520
what is right and wrong,
or that we need God

01:24:55.520 --> 01:24:57.430
to tell us what is right and wrong,

01:24:57.430 --> 01:24:59.310
it's rather that we need
to have some sort of

01:24:59.310 --> 01:25:02.080
an objective foundation
for right and wrong.

01:25:02.080 --> 01:25:05.520
Wouldn't you agree on
your view it's simply the

01:25:05.520 --> 01:25:08.250
socio-biological spinoffs
of the evolutionary

01:25:08.250 --> 01:25:10.639
process and that therefore
these do not provide

01:25:10.639 --> 01:25:14.510
any sort of objective foundation

01:25:14.510 --> 01:25:16.463
for moral values and duties?

01:25:17.360 --> 01:25:19.790
&gt;&gt; That could be true, yes.

01:25:19.790 --> 01:25:20.869
&gt;&gt; William: Okay.

01:25:20.869 --> 01:25:21.702
&gt;&gt; Could well be true.

01:25:21.702 --> 01:25:22.535
Yeah.

01:25:22.535 --> 01:25:24.260
I don't want to be too
much of a reductionist,

01:25:24.260 --> 01:25:26.550
but it's entirely
possible that it is purely

01:25:26.550 --> 01:25:27.950
evolutionary and functional.

01:25:27.950 --> 01:25:29.750
One wants to think that
there's a bit more to

01:25:29.750 --> 01:25:32.200
one's love for the fellow
creature than that.

01:25:32.200 --> 01:25:35.831
But it doesn't add one iota of weight

01:25:35.831 --> 01:25:39.120
or moral gravity to the
argument to say that's

01:25:39.120 --> 01:25:41.847
because I don't believe
in a supernatural being.

01:25:41.847 --> 01:25:42.847
It's a non sequitur.

01:25:43.739 --> 01:25:45.730
&gt;&gt; Hugh: Mr. Hitchens, your
questions for Dr. Craig.

01:25:45.730 --> 01:25:48.900
&gt;&gt; Ah, well, I'd like to know first,

01:25:48.900 --> 01:25:49.790
you said

01:25:52.230 --> 01:25:55.130
that the career of Jesus
of Nazareth involved

01:25:55.130 --> 01:25:57.553
a ministry of miracles and exorcisms.

01:25:58.450 --> 01:26:01.390
When you say "exorcism,"
do you mean that you

01:26:01.390 --> 01:26:02.910
believe in devils too?

01:26:02.910 --> 01:26:05.110
&gt;&gt; What I meant there
was that most historians

01:26:05.110 --> 01:26:09.019
agree that Jesus of Nazareth
practiced miracle working

01:26:09.019 --> 01:26:11.140
and he practiced exorcisms.

01:26:11.140 --> 01:26:12.970
I'm not committing myself,

01:26:12.970 --> 01:26:15.240
nor are historians committing themselves,

01:26:15.240 --> 01:26:17.350
to the reality of demons
but they are saying

01:26:17.350 --> 01:26:22.350
that Jesus did practice exorcism
and he practiced healing.

01:26:24.320 --> 01:26:28.550
&gt;&gt; So you believe that Jesus of Nazareth

01:26:28.550 --> 01:26:31.410
caused devils to leave
the body of a madman

01:26:31.410 --> 01:26:34.790
and go into a flock of
pigs that hurled themselves

01:26:34.790 --> 01:26:36.690
down the Gadarene slopes into the sea?

01:26:36.690 --> 01:26:38.820
&gt;&gt; Do I believe that's historical?

01:26:38.820 --> 01:26:39.653
Yes.

01:26:39.653 --> 01:26:41.030
&gt;&gt; Christopher: Right.

01:26:41.030 --> 01:26:43.600
That would be sorcery wouldn't it, though?

01:26:43.600 --> 01:26:46.790
&gt;&gt; No, it would be an
illustration of Jesus'

01:26:46.790 --> 01:26:49.710
ability to command even
the forces of darkness

01:26:49.710 --> 01:26:51.930
and therefore an illustration of the sort

01:26:51.930 --> 01:26:54.470
of divine authority that he was able

01:26:54.470 --> 01:26:55.800
to command and exercise.

01:26:55.800 --> 01:27:00.730
This, as I say, is illustrative
of this unprecedented

01:27:00.730 --> 01:27:04.260
sense of divine authority
that Jesus of Nazareth

01:27:04.260 --> 01:27:06.505
had that he even could command the forces

01:27:06.505 --> 01:27:09.380
of darkness and that they would obey.

01:27:09.380 --> 01:27:13.240
So, whether you think he
was a genuine exorcist

01:27:13.240 --> 01:27:16.000
or that he merely believed
himself to be an exorcist,

01:27:16.000 --> 01:27:18.250
what is historically undeniable is that he

01:27:18.250 --> 01:27:22.630
had this radical sense of divine authority

01:27:22.630 --> 01:27:26.480
which he expressed by miracle
working and exorcisms.

01:27:26.480 --> 01:27:27.313
&gt;&gt; Right.

01:27:27.313 --> 01:27:30.360
And do you believe he
was born of a virgin?

01:27:30.360 --> 01:27:31.490
&gt;&gt; Um.

01:27:31.490 --> 01:27:33.850
Yes, I believe that as a Christian.

01:27:33.850 --> 01:27:35.970
I couldn't claim to
prove that, historically.

01:27:35.970 --> 01:27:38.060
That's not part of my case tonight.

01:27:38.060 --> 01:27:40.560
But I, as a Christian, I believe that.

01:27:40.560 --> 01:27:42.581
&gt;&gt; And I know you believe
in the resurrection but--

01:27:42.581 --> 01:27:45.340
&gt;&gt; Williams: Yes, that I
think we have good evidence.

01:27:45.340 --> 01:27:47.790
&gt;&gt; As a matter of biblical,
what shall we call it,

01:27:48.860 --> 01:27:51.440
consistency, it's said
in one of the Gospels

01:27:51.440 --> 01:27:53.050
that at the time of the crucifixion

01:27:53.050 --> 01:27:54.666
all the graves of Jerusalem were opened

01:27:54.666 --> 01:27:57.700
and all the tenants of the
graves walked the streets

01:27:57.700 --> 01:27:58.640
and greeted their old friends.

01:27:58.640 --> 01:28:00.990
It makes resurrection
sound rather commonplace

01:28:00.990 --> 01:28:02.892
in the greater Jerusalem area.

01:28:02.892 --> 01:28:05.340
&gt;&gt; That's in the gospel of
Matthew and that's actually

01:28:05.340 --> 01:28:08.076
attached to a crucifixion
narrative where--

01:28:08.076 --> 01:28:09.076
&gt;&gt; Christopher: That's what I said,

01:28:09.076 --> 01:28:09.909
it says at the time of the crucifixion.

01:28:09.909 --> 01:28:11.300
&gt;&gt; Yes, that's right, at
the time of the crucifixion

01:28:11.300 --> 01:28:14.104
it says that there were
appearances of Old Testament

01:28:14.104 --> 01:28:16.830
saints in Jerusalem at the time.

01:28:16.830 --> 01:28:19.460
This is part of Matthew's description

01:28:19.460 --> 01:28:21.390
of the crucifixion scene.

01:28:21.390 --> 01:28:22.900
&gt;&gt; Christopher: I mean,
do you believe that?

01:28:22.900 --> 01:28:25.010
&gt;&gt; I don't know whether
Matthew intends this to be

01:28:25.010 --> 01:28:27.690
apocalyptic imagery or
whether he means this

01:28:27.690 --> 01:28:28.670
to be taken literally.

01:28:28.670 --> 01:28:30.610
I've not studied it in any depth

01:28:30.610 --> 01:28:32.360
and I'm open minded about it.

01:28:32.360 --> 01:28:34.287
I'm willing to be convinced
one way or the other.

01:28:34.287 --> 01:28:35.690
&gt;&gt; You see the reason
I'm pressing you is this:

01:28:35.690 --> 01:28:37.470
Because, I mean, we know from Scripture

01:28:37.470 --> 01:28:40.890
that Pharoahs' magicians
could produce miracles.

01:28:40.890 --> 01:28:42.650
In the end, Aaron could outproduce them,

01:28:42.650 --> 01:28:43.820
but what I'm suggesting to you is even

01:28:43.820 --> 01:28:45.980
if the laws of nature can be suspended

01:28:45.980 --> 01:28:50.310
and great miracles can be performed,

01:28:50.310 --> 01:28:51.820
it doesn't prove the truth of the doctrine

01:28:51.820 --> 01:28:53.620
of the person who's performing them.

01:28:54.523 --> 01:28:55.780
Would you not agree to that?

01:28:55.780 --> 01:28:58.800
&gt;&gt; William: Not necessarily,
I think that's right.

01:28:58.800 --> 01:29:01.267
&gt;&gt; So somebody could be
casting out devils from pigs

01:29:01.267 --> 01:29:03.530
and that wouldn't prove
he was the son of God?

01:29:03.530 --> 01:29:04.420
&gt;&gt; I think that's right.

01:29:04.420 --> 01:29:06.170
In fact, there were Jewish exorcists.

01:29:06.170 --> 01:29:09.110
The only point that I was
trying to make there was,

01:29:09.110 --> 01:29:11.800
that this was illustrative of the kind

01:29:11.800 --> 01:29:14.470
of divine authority that Jesus claimed,

01:29:14.470 --> 01:29:16.281
especially since He didn't cast them out--

01:29:16.281 --> 01:29:17.114
&gt;&gt; Christopher: But if--

01:29:17.114 --> 01:29:19.370
&gt;&gt; In God's name or He
didn't perform miracles

01:29:19.370 --> 01:29:23.080
by praying to God, He would
do them in His own authority,

01:29:23.080 --> 01:29:27.377
so that Jesus exercised an
authority that was simply

01:29:27.377 --> 01:29:31.451
unheard of at that time and,
for which He was eventually

01:29:31.451 --> 01:29:35.103
crucified because it was
thought to be blasphemous.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:37.060
&gt;&gt; Well, it was though to be blasphemous

01:29:37.060 --> 01:29:38.320
to have claimed to be
the Messiah, to be exact.

01:29:38.320 --> 01:29:40.640
I mean, the people who got
the closest look at him,

01:29:40.640 --> 01:29:43.168
the Jewish Sanhedrin,
thought that his claims were

01:29:43.168 --> 01:29:46.240
not genuine so, remember,
if you're resting anything

01:29:46.240 --> 01:29:48.043
on eye witnesses, the ones
who we definitely know

01:29:48.043 --> 01:29:51.010
were there thought he was bogus.

01:29:51.010 --> 01:29:53.240
But okay, I think I've got a rough idea.

01:29:53.240 --> 01:29:55.640
Assuming you make that assumption of

01:29:55.640 --> 01:29:57.100
his pre-existing divinity,

01:29:57.100 --> 01:29:59.730
that it's a presuppositionalist case,

01:29:59.730 --> 01:30:00.930
I can see what you're driving at.

01:30:00.930 --> 01:30:02.220
&gt;&gt; Well no, I'm not a presuppositionalist.

01:30:02.220 --> 01:30:04.120
&gt;&gt; I've got another question
for you, which is this:

01:30:04.120 --> 01:30:07.140
How many religions in the world
do you believe to be false?

01:30:07.140 --> 01:30:08.970
&gt;&gt; I don't know how many
religions in the world

01:30:08.970 --> 01:30:13.614
there are, so I can't--
[audience laughing]

01:30:13.614 --> 01:30:14.864
&gt;&gt; Fair enough.

01:30:14.864 --> 01:30:17.073
I'll see if I can't narrow that down.

01:30:18.400 --> 01:30:20.780
That was a clumsily asked
question, I'll admit.

01:30:20.780 --> 01:30:23.693
Do you regard any of the
world's religions to be false?

01:30:23.693 --> 01:30:24.693
&gt;&gt; William: Excuse me?

01:30:24.693 --> 01:30:25.526
&gt;&gt; Do you regard any of
the world's religions

01:30:25.526 --> 01:30:26.359
to be false preaching?

01:30:26.359 --> 01:30:28.700
&gt;&gt; William: Yes, yes, I think, certainly.

01:30:28.700 --> 01:30:30.100
&gt;&gt; Would you name one then?

01:30:30.100 --> 01:30:30.980
&gt;&gt; Islam.

01:30:30.980 --> 01:30:32.580
&gt;&gt; Christopher: That's quite a lot.

01:30:32.580 --> 01:30:33.413
&gt;&gt; Pardon me?

01:30:33.413 --> 01:30:34.246
&gt;&gt; Christopher: That's quite a lot.

01:30:34.246 --> 01:30:35.150
&gt;&gt; Yes.

01:30:35.150 --> 01:30:36.430
&gt;&gt; Christopher: Therefore,
do you think it's moral

01:30:36.430 --> 01:30:38.090
to preach false religion?

01:30:38.090 --> 01:30:38.923
&gt;&gt; No.

01:30:38.923 --> 01:30:39.820
&gt;&gt; Christopher: So religion
is responsible for quite

01:30:39.820 --> 01:30:41.180
a lot of wickedness in
the world right there?

01:30:41.180 --> 01:30:42.180
&gt;&gt; Certainly.

01:30:42.180 --> 01:30:45.280
I'd be happy to concede that,
I would agree with that.

01:30:45.280 --> 01:30:48.910
&gt;&gt; So if I was a baby being
born in Saudi Arabia today,

01:30:48.910 --> 01:30:52.113
would you rather I was
me, or a Wahabi Muslim?

01:30:53.237 --> 01:30:55.129
&gt;&gt; Would you rather be what?
[audience laughing]

01:30:55.129 --> 01:30:58.700
&gt;&gt; Would you rather it was
me, it was an atheist baby,

01:30:58.700 --> 01:31:03.033
or a Wahabi baby?
[audience laughing]

01:31:06.130 --> 01:31:11.130
&gt;&gt; I don't have any, uh,
preference as to whether you--

01:31:11.597 --> 01:31:15.788
[audience laughing]
[applause]

01:31:15.788 --> 01:31:18.323
&gt;&gt; As bad as that, okay.

01:31:20.360 --> 01:31:21.403
Are there any,

01:31:22.426 --> 01:31:24.590
sorry, I've only got a few seconds.

01:31:24.590 --> 01:31:26.720
It's a serious question,
I should squander it.

01:31:26.720 --> 01:31:29.550
Are there any Christian
denominations you regard as false?

01:31:29.550 --> 01:31:30.590
&gt;&gt; William: Certainly.

01:31:30.590 --> 01:31:32.100
&gt;&gt; Christopher: Could
I know what they are?

01:31:32.100 --> 01:31:33.103
&gt;&gt; Um.

01:31:34.530 --> 01:31:39.130
Well, uh, I'm not a
Calvinist, for example.

01:31:39.130 --> 01:31:41.550
I think that certain tenets of

01:31:41.550 --> 01:31:43.800
Reformed Theology are incorrect.

01:31:43.800 --> 01:31:48.140
I would be more in Wesleyan camp myself.

01:31:48.140 --> 01:31:51.260
But, these are differences among brethren.

01:31:51.260 --> 01:31:54.660
these are not difference on which we need

01:31:54.660 --> 01:31:56.750
to put one another into
some sort of a cage.

01:31:56.750 --> 01:31:58.660
So, within the Christian camp,

01:31:58.660 --> 01:32:01.160
there's a large diversity of perspectives.

01:32:01.160 --> 01:32:02.750
I'm sure there are views that I hold

01:32:02.750 --> 01:32:05.573
that are probably false
but I'm trying my best

01:32:05.573 --> 01:32:09.050
to get my theology straight,
trying to do the best job

01:32:09.050 --> 01:32:11.650
but I think all of us
would recognize that none

01:32:11.650 --> 01:32:14.790
of us agree on every point
of Christian doctrine,

01:32:14.790 --> 01:32:17.730
on every dot and tittle.

01:32:17.730 --> 01:32:20.470
&gt;&gt; Before Mr. Hitchens
succeeds in launching another

01:32:20.470 --> 01:32:23.785
series of religious wars among
Christians let's get to the--

01:32:23.785 --> 01:32:25.867
[audience laughing]

01:32:25.867 --> 01:32:28.950
Let's get to the responses,
seven minutes each.

01:32:28.950 --> 01:32:31.599
Dr. Craig, it is your seven minutes.

01:32:31.599 --> 01:32:32.432
&gt;&gt; Okay.

01:32:33.533 --> 01:32:36.866
[William clears throat]

01:32:52.490 --> 01:32:55.290
Well, I think it's very evident
that in tonight's debate,

01:32:55.290 --> 01:32:58.960
we've not heard any good
reasons to think that what is

01:32:58.960 --> 01:33:01.640
normally called atheism is true,

01:33:01.640 --> 01:33:04.090
that is to say the belief
that God does notexist.

01:33:05.750 --> 01:33:09.800
Mr. Hitchens withholds
belief in God but he's unable

01:33:09.800 --> 01:33:12.140
to give us any argument to think that God

01:33:12.140 --> 01:33:16.700
does not exist which is what
is called positive atheism.

01:33:16.700 --> 01:33:18.850
Now he does mention that the human species

01:33:18.850 --> 01:33:21.950
has been here for 100,000 years but I've

01:33:21.950 --> 01:33:23.160
already responded to that.

01:33:23.160 --> 01:33:26.000
What's crucial there is
not the number of years,

01:33:26.000 --> 01:33:29.710
it's the population and only
two percent of the population

01:33:29.710 --> 01:33:32.040
of the earth has existed before Christ.

01:33:32.040 --> 01:33:34.840
And during that time
God is not indifferent

01:33:34.840 --> 01:33:38.410
to the lot of those people,
rather he is preparing humanity,

01:33:38.410 --> 01:33:41.320
preparing the world for
the advent of Christ

01:33:41.320 --> 01:33:43.940
so that in the fullness
of time Christ would come

01:33:43.940 --> 01:33:44.980
into the world.

01:33:44.980 --> 01:33:47.870
And those people who
lived apart from Christ,

01:33:47.870 --> 01:33:50.290
God cared for them as well
and provided for them.

01:33:50.290 --> 01:33:53.947
The Bible says, "Ever since
the creation of the world,

01:33:53.947 --> 01:33:57.327
"God's invisible nature,
namely His eternal power

01:33:57.327 --> 01:34:00.040
"and deity has been clearly
perceived in the things

01:34:00.040 --> 01:34:01.505
"that have been made."

01:34:01.505 --> 01:34:05.967
Paul says that, "From one man
God made every nation of men,

01:34:05.967 --> 01:34:08.127
"that they should inhabit the whole earth

01:34:08.127 --> 01:34:10.617
"and He determined the time set for them

01:34:10.617 --> 01:34:13.657
"in the exact places
that they should live.

01:34:13.657 --> 01:34:17.617
"He did this so men would
seek Him and perhaps reach out

01:34:17.617 --> 01:34:21.177
"for Him and find Him, for
He is not far from each

01:34:21.177 --> 01:34:25.370
"one of us, for in Him we live
and move and have our being."

01:34:25.370 --> 01:34:28.530
So that those who lived
before Christ were covered

01:34:28.530 --> 01:34:30.270
by the death of Christ, they were covered

01:34:30.270 --> 01:34:34.084
by his atoning sacrifice
and God will judge them

01:34:34.084 --> 01:34:36.150
on the basis of the information that

01:34:36.150 --> 01:34:39.020
they had in their response
to general revelation.

01:34:39.020 --> 01:34:42.440
Similar to those who haven't
heard the Gospel yet today,

01:34:42.440 --> 01:34:45.850
they will be judged on the
basis of the information that

01:34:45.850 --> 01:34:48.050
they do have and how they respond to that.

01:34:48.050 --> 01:34:50.990
And aren't you glad that you
don't have to judge them?

01:34:50.990 --> 01:34:54.270
You can leave this up
to the hands of a just

01:34:54.270 --> 01:34:57.350
and holy and merciful
God who will judge people

01:34:57.350 --> 01:35:00.088
on the basis of how they
respond to the revelation

01:35:00.088 --> 01:35:02.080
that they do have.

01:35:02.080 --> 01:35:05.110
So we've not heard any
argument tonight that God

01:35:05.110 --> 01:35:06.550
does not exist.

01:35:06.550 --> 01:35:09.010
Now, by contrast, I've
given five arguments

01:35:09.010 --> 01:35:11.270
to show that Christian theism is true.

01:35:11.270 --> 01:35:14.323
First, we saw the cosmological argument.

01:35:15.210 --> 01:35:17.980
Mr. Hitchens has not disagreed with either

01:35:17.980 --> 01:35:20.460
of the premises of this
argument and so we have

01:35:20.460 --> 01:35:22.810
good grounds to believe
in the personal creator

01:35:22.810 --> 01:35:24.090
of the universe.

01:35:24.090 --> 01:35:27.770
As for the teleological
argument, again he didn't

01:35:27.770 --> 01:35:30.240
respond to what I said in my last speech

01:35:30.240 --> 01:35:34.110
with respect to the fine
tuning being well established

01:35:34.110 --> 01:35:38.020
in science and that the
fact that we're going

01:35:38.020 --> 01:35:39.530
towards nothingness as he puts it,

01:35:39.530 --> 01:35:43.240
is an atheistic assumption,
not a Christian assumption

01:35:43.240 --> 01:35:46.238
and therefore doesn't do
anything to disprove design.

01:35:46.238 --> 01:35:48.100
Now what about the moral argument?

01:35:48.100 --> 01:35:51.607
Here he says that, "You have
to prove that people would

01:35:51.607 --> 01:35:54.560
"behave better if they believed in God."

01:35:54.560 --> 01:35:57.960
That's not the argument, I
hope that's clear to everyone.

01:35:57.960 --> 01:36:01.176
The argument is that without
God as a transcendent

01:36:01.176 --> 01:36:03.540
foundation for moral values,

01:36:03.540 --> 01:36:07.060
we're simply lost in
socio-cultural relativism.

01:36:07.060 --> 01:36:10.220
Who are you to judge that
the Nazi ethic was wrong?

01:36:10.220 --> 01:36:12.330
Who are you to judge
that the ethic of ancient

01:36:12.330 --> 01:36:13.380
Hinduism was wrong?

01:36:13.380 --> 01:36:17.990
Who are you to judge that the
Africana apartheid is wrong?

01:36:17.990 --> 01:36:20.250
This is all just the
result of socio-cultural

01:36:20.250 --> 01:36:23.100
evolution and there is
no transcendent objective

01:36:23.100 --> 01:36:27.810
standard apart from God and
that's what God delivers for us.

01:36:27.810 --> 01:36:28.857
Now Mr. Hitchens says,

01:36:28.857 --> 01:36:32.300
"Name one moral action that
an unbeliever could not take."

01:36:32.300 --> 01:36:34.260
Well, that's trivially easy.

01:36:34.260 --> 01:36:36.680
If God exists there are
all kinds of moral duties

01:36:36.680 --> 01:36:39.580
that we have that the
unbeliever cannot recognize.

01:36:39.580 --> 01:36:41.800
At the panel discussion
last week in Dallas,

01:36:41.800 --> 01:36:45.980
when Mr. Hitchens demanded that
someone name such an action,

01:36:45.980 --> 01:36:48.797
a pastor on the panel
immediately piped up,

01:36:48.797 --> 01:36:52.400
"How about tithing?"
[audience laughing]

01:36:52.400 --> 01:36:57.296
Well, leave it to a pastor to
think of that, but, clearly,

01:36:57.296 --> 01:37:01.490
that's an action that only
a believer would take.

01:37:01.490 --> 01:37:03.500
Even more fundamentally,
what about the first

01:37:03.500 --> 01:37:04.817
and greatest commandment?

01:37:04.817 --> 01:37:07.747
"You shall love the Lord
your God with all your heart,

01:37:07.747 --> 01:37:10.260
"with all your strength,
with all your mind."

01:37:10.260 --> 01:37:13.320
That is an action that
only a believer can take,

01:37:13.320 --> 01:37:15.840
no unbeliever can discharge even this most

01:37:15.840 --> 01:37:18.500
fundamental of moral duties.

01:37:18.500 --> 01:37:21.280
But, in any case, all of this is beside

01:37:21.280 --> 01:37:23.740
the point with respect
to the moral argument.

01:37:23.740 --> 01:37:26.190
The point is that on atheism there are

01:37:26.190 --> 01:37:29.770
no moral obligations
for anybody to fulfill.

01:37:29.770 --> 01:37:33.770
In nature, whatever is,
is right and Mr. Hitchens

01:37:33.770 --> 01:37:37.867
is unable to provide any
sort of objective foundation

01:37:37.867 --> 01:37:39.812
for moral values.

01:37:39.812 --> 01:37:43.910
Massimo Pigliucci is a
philosopher of biology.

01:37:43.910 --> 01:37:45.780
This is what he has to say.

01:37:45.780 --> 01:37:47.777
He says on atheism,
"There is no such thing

01:37:47.777 --> 01:37:49.427
"as objective morality.

01:37:49.427 --> 01:37:51.647
"Morality in human cultures has evolved

01:37:51.647 --> 01:37:53.817
"and what is moral for
you might not be moral

01:37:53.817 --> 01:37:56.597
"for the guy next door
and certainly is not moral

01:37:56.597 --> 01:37:58.227
"for the guy across the ocean.

01:37:58.227 --> 01:38:00.687
"And what makes you think
that your personal morality

01:38:00.687 --> 01:38:03.067
"is the one and everybody else is wrong?

01:38:03.067 --> 01:38:05.687
"What we call homicide or rape," he said,

01:38:05.687 --> 01:38:09.087
"Is very, very common among
different kinds of animals.

01:38:09.087 --> 01:38:13.287
"Lions, for example, commit
infanticide on a regular basis.

01:38:13.287 --> 01:38:15.797
"Now, are these kinds
of acts to be condoned?

01:38:15.797 --> 01:38:17.577
"I don't even know what that means because

01:38:17.577 --> 01:38:20.267
"the lion doesn't
understand what morality is.

01:38:20.267 --> 01:38:23.650
"Morality," he says, "Is an
invention of human beings."

01:38:23.650 --> 01:38:25.670
It's just a convention that human beings

01:38:25.670 --> 01:38:27.500
have adopted to live together.

01:38:27.500 --> 01:38:29.470
But it has no objectivity.

01:38:29.470 --> 01:38:32.070
And that's what I offer
Mr. Hitchens tonight,

01:38:32.070 --> 01:38:35.840
is a solid, transcendent
foundation for the moral values

01:38:35.840 --> 01:38:38.403
that I think he so
desperately wants to affirm.

01:38:39.650 --> 01:38:41.870
What about the resurrection of Jesus?

01:38:41.870 --> 01:38:44.630
Here he misunderstood
N.T. Wright's argument.

01:38:44.630 --> 01:38:46.970
N.T. Wright's argument
is not that the success

01:38:46.970 --> 01:38:49.380
of Christianity means that it's true,

01:38:49.380 --> 01:38:51.910
that would apply to Islam and Mormonism,

01:38:51.910 --> 01:38:53.910
rather, N.T. Wright's argument is that

01:38:53.910 --> 01:38:56.290
the origin of the disciples' belief that

01:38:56.290 --> 01:39:00.480
God had raised Jesus from
the dead is so un-Jewish,

01:39:00.480 --> 01:39:02.930
it is so uncharacteristic,

01:39:02.930 --> 01:39:06.600
that you have to explain
what would bring them

01:39:06.600 --> 01:39:10.630
to adopt so radical a
mutation of Jewish belief,

01:39:10.630 --> 01:39:14.720
as belief in a dying Messiah
and a rising Messiah.

01:39:14.720 --> 01:39:16.930
And he says the only thing
he can think of that would

01:39:16.930 --> 01:39:19.210
explain this is the empty tomb and

01:39:19.210 --> 01:39:22.000
the post mortem appearances
of Jesus and that's why

01:39:22.000 --> 01:39:23.460
Wright concludes that these have

01:39:23.460 --> 01:39:26.130
a certainty that is comparable to the fall

01:39:26.130 --> 01:39:28.420
of Jerusalem in AD 70.

01:39:28.420 --> 01:39:30.450
So you've gotta get the argument right if

01:39:30.450 --> 01:39:32.960
you're going to deal with it and, in fact,

01:39:32.960 --> 01:39:35.690
I think the only
explanation of these facts

01:39:35.690 --> 01:39:37.930
is the one that the
disciples gave that God

01:39:37.930 --> 01:39:39.660
raised Jesus from the dead.

01:39:39.660 --> 01:39:42.230
Finally, the immediate experience of God

01:39:42.230 --> 01:39:43.340
has remained untouched.

01:39:43.340 --> 01:39:44.683
God is real to me.

01:39:45.690 --> 01:39:47.130
And unless I'm delusional,

01:39:47.130 --> 01:39:49.110
I'm perfectly within my rational rights

01:39:49.110 --> 01:39:52.440
to believe in God on the
basis of this experience

01:39:52.440 --> 01:39:55.730
just as I believe in the
reality of the external world

01:39:55.730 --> 01:39:59.210
or the reality of the past on
the basis of my experience.

01:39:59.210 --> 01:40:01.560
So I think in sum, we've
got five good reasons

01:40:01.560 --> 01:40:04.010
for believing that Christianity is true,

01:40:04.010 --> 01:40:06.430
no reason to think atheism is true

01:40:06.430 --> 01:40:07.960
and therefore I think Christianity

01:40:07.960 --> 01:40:10.300
is clearly the more rational world view.

01:40:11.916 --> 01:40:14.916
[audience applause]

01:40:25.684 --> 01:40:27.990
&gt;&gt; I think, you'll
correct me if I'm wrong,

01:40:27.990 --> 01:40:31.980
it's Tertilian, isn't it,
who says something like,

01:40:31.980 --> 01:40:35.050
it's variously translated
"credo quia absurdum?"

01:40:35.050 --> 01:40:38.480
That the very improbability of the thing,

01:40:38.480 --> 01:40:41.180
the very unlikelihood of
it, the unlikelihood that

01:40:41.180 --> 01:40:43.630
anyone would fabricate
such a thing, for example,

01:40:43.630 --> 01:40:45.490
that a Jew could be brought to believe

01:40:45.490 --> 01:40:49.250
something so extraordinary,
is testimony to its truth.

01:40:49.250 --> 01:40:51.050
I'm sure there can't be
anyone here who doesn't thinks

01:40:51.050 --> 01:40:53.830
that's a little too easy,
a little too facile.

01:40:53.830 --> 01:40:55.890
I myself, for example,
have followed the career

01:40:55.890 --> 01:41:00.650
of a woman known vulgarly in
the media as "Mother Teresa,"

01:41:00.650 --> 01:41:05.190
an Albanian named Agnes
Bojaxhiu, a Catholic fanatic

01:41:05.190 --> 01:41:08.400
operating in the greater Calcutta area,

01:41:08.400 --> 01:41:13.400
and I watched every stage of
her career as a candidate for,

01:41:13.894 --> 01:41:17.560
and then the recipient of, beatification

01:41:17.560 --> 01:41:19.250
and shortly, canonization.

01:41:19.250 --> 01:41:24.223
The canonization will require,
as the Vatican demands,

01:41:25.232 --> 01:41:26.820
the attestation of a miracle performed

01:41:26.820 --> 01:41:29.380
by her posthumous intercession.

01:41:29.380 --> 01:41:31.570
And the miracle's already been announced,

01:41:31.570 --> 01:41:35.460
a woman in Bengal, fortunately
already a devout Catholic,

01:41:35.460 --> 01:41:38.550
by pressing a medal of
Mother Teresa to her stomach,

01:41:38.550 --> 01:41:42.027
made a tumor go away, or so she says.

01:41:42.027 --> 01:41:44.990
All the witnesses to
this have since recanted,

01:41:44.990 --> 01:41:46.980
all the doctors have given
a much better explanation

01:41:46.980 --> 01:41:49.309
of how she was cured of
the swelling and the growth

01:41:49.309 --> 01:41:51.150
and what the medicines were and so forth,

01:41:51.150 --> 01:41:52.620
but they're still stuck with it.

01:41:52.620 --> 01:41:55.780
They have to go ahead
with this process because,

01:41:55.780 --> 01:41:58.550
which will lead to
countless, untold suffering

01:41:58.550 --> 01:42:00.330
in India because it will appear to license

01:42:00.330 --> 01:42:03.290
the bogus charlatanry of shaman,

01:42:03.290 --> 01:42:06.630
medicine and intercessory medicine rather

01:42:06.630 --> 01:42:07.580
than the real thing.

01:42:07.580 --> 01:42:09.880
All of this will have to be gone through,

01:42:09.880 --> 01:42:13.400
this awful display, in the name of faith.

01:42:13.400 --> 01:42:15.627
And I just happened to have
watched it at every stage

01:42:15.627 --> 01:42:19.260
and I can tell you it's depressingly easy

01:42:19.260 --> 01:42:21.740
to get a religious rumor started.

01:42:21.740 --> 01:42:25.478
You can count on an enormous
amount of pre-existing

01:42:25.478 --> 01:42:29.230
credulity among illiterate, frightened,

01:42:29.230 --> 01:42:30.950
ill-educated populations.

01:42:30.950 --> 01:42:33.960
There isn't a literate, written-down,

01:42:33.960 --> 01:42:38.960
